{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018SxMr6mJRoDRNGfhEVb8ZE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 28 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Draft\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5→**Based on:** Iteration 27 feedback (11 failures, all generated files)\n     6→\n     7→## Problem Statement\n     8→\n     9→Iteration 27 scores 90.1% overall (100% on real files, plateau on generated). The 11 remaining failures cluster into 4 patterns that share a common root: the pipeline rejects or misranks the true title line, then falls back to garbage. The current codebase is ~1500 lines of layered heuristics. Each fix risks regressions in other branches of the logic. The patterns are well-understood and each has a targeted fix that doesn't require architectural changes.\n    10→\n    11→## Goals\n    12→\n    13→- Fix all 4 failure patterns without regressing existing passing tests\n    14→- Keep changes minimal and targeted — the architecture works, the edge cases don't\n    15→\n    16→## Non-Goals\n    17→\n    18→- Replacing the embedding-based approach (it works well for 90%+ of cases)\n    19→- Reducing overall code complexity (a separate effort)\n    20→- Handling new patterns not seen in iteration 27\n    21→\n    22→---\n    23→\n    24→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter corruption on title line (5 cases)\n    25→\n    26→**Cases:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski\n    27→\n    28→**Root cause:** `repairOcrText` only repairs words found in `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. When a corrupted word like `Bra1sed` or `D1p` has no dictionary match, it passes through unrepaired. The corrupted text then either:\n    29→- Gets a low embedding score (MiniLM doesn't understand `Bra1sed`) and loses to later candidates\n    30→- Falls below the threshold entirely, resulting in empty output\n    31→- Gets beaten by garbage text that happens to embed slightly better\n    32→\n    33→**Fix: Blind OCR repair for early-position candidates**\n    34→\n    35→The existing `normalizeOcrTitle` already does blind digit→letter substitution (1→I, 4→A, 5→S, 0→O) but only as post-processing on the *winner*. The fix is to apply the same blind repair *before* embedding, specifically for candidates in the first few lines where positional evidence is strong.\n    36→\n    37→### Implementation\n    38→\n    39→In `buildCandidates`, after constructing each single-line candidate from the first 3 non-empty lines, generate a second \"OCR-repaired\" variant using blind substitution (the same logic as `normalizeOcrTitle` step 2). If the repaired text differs from the original AND passes hard filters, add it as an additional candidate at the same position. This gives the embedding scorer a clean version to work with.\n    40→\n    41→```typescript\n    42→// In buildCandidates, after adding the single-line candidate:\n    43→if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(singleText)) {\n    44→  const blindRepaired = applyBlindOcrRepair(singleText);\n    45→  if (blindRepaired !== singleText && passesHardFilters(blindRepaired)) {\n    46→    const norm = blindRepaired.toLowerCase();\n    47→    if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n    48→      seen.add(norm);\n    49→      candidates.push({ text: blindRepaired, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n    50→    }\n    51→  }\n    52→}\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→Extract the blind substitution logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` into a reusable `applyBlindOcrRepair` function. This function applies:\n    56→- `1` → `I` (in ALL_CAPS) or `l`/`i` (in mixed case, context-dependent)\n    57→- `4` → `A`\n    58→- `5` → `S`\n    59→- `0` → `O` (when adjacent to letters)\n    60→\n    61→**Why this works:** The true title at line 1 with `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` becomes `Braised Cod with White Wine` after blind repair. This clean version embeds well and gets a high title similarity score. The original corrupted version also stays in the pool as a fallback. The position bonus for early candidates ensures the repaired version outscores garbage text later in the file.\n    62→\n    63→**Risk:** Blind repair could create false words (e.g., `H1GH` → `HIGH` when the original was a code). Mitigated by limiting to the first 5 lines (title region) and by requiring the repaired text to pass all hard filters.\n    64→\n    65→---\n    66→\n    67→## Pattern 2: Category/section header precedes the title (3 cases)\n    68→\n    69→**Cases:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n    70→\n    71→**Root cause:** Two sub-problems:\n    72→\n    73→1. **After skipping a section header, the first-after-preamble bonus fires but isn't decisive enough.** The bonus (+0.08 to +0.12) can be outweighed by a longer candidate deeper in the file that has higher embedding similarity. For example, a description sentence about halibut may embed closer to \"recipe title\" than the actual title because it contains more food-related words.\n    74→\n    75→2. **Pipe-separated metadata lines (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...`) are filtered by the existing `text.includes(\" | \")` hard filter, BUT the individual segments after splitting are not.** When the pipe-separated line is filtered, the next line should be the title. However, if the pipe line contains segments that individually pass hard filters (e.g., `Lato` as a standalone word — wait, that's filtered by word length. Actually the pipe line IS already filtered. The issue is more subtle: the metadata line gets filtered, but the *next* line (the actual title) doesn't get the first-after-preamble bonus because there's other content between the metadata and the title that also passes as candidates.\n    76→\n    77→**Fix: Strengthen post-header title promotion**\n    78→\n    79→The first-after-preamble bonus currently checks whether ALL preceding lines were filtered. If any non-filtered line exists before the first candidate, the bonus doesn't fire. The fix: extend the bonus to fire when the *immediately preceding* line (not all preceding lines) was a section label or metadata, regardless of what came before that.\n    80→\n    81→### Implementation\n    82→\n    83→Add a \"direct-successor\" bonus in the scoring pass:\n    84→\n    85→```typescript\n    86→// After existing first-after-preamble logic:\n    87→// Direct successor bonus: if the line immediately before this candidate\n    88→// is a section label, metadata, or pipe-separated line, this candidate\n    89→// is very likely the title that follows that header.\n    90→if (candidate.position > 0) {\n    91→  const prevLine = lines[candidate.position - 1]?.trim() ?? \"\";\n    92→  const prevIsHeader = isSectionLabel(prevLine) ||\n    93→                       looksLikeMetadata(prevLine) ||\n    94→                       prevLine.includes(\" | \");\n    95→  if (prevIsHeader && candidateIndex <= 2) {\n    96→    candidate.score += 0.10;\n    97→    candidate.baseScore += 0.10;\n    98→    candidate.thresholdScore += 0.10;\n    99→  }\n   100→}\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→The `candidateIndex <= 2` guard prevents the bonus from firing on random mid-document candidates that happen to follow a metadata line.\n   104→\n   105→**Why this works:** For `FISH & SEAFOOD\\nHalibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`, the header is filtered, and \"Halibut...\" is the first candidate. It gets both the existing first-after-preamble bonus AND the direct-successor bonus, making it decisively outscore description text later in the file.\n   106→\n   107→For `Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\\nOgórkowa Zupa`, the pipe line is filtered, and \"Ogórkowa Zupa\" immediately follows and gets the direct-successor bonus.\n   108→\n   109→**Risk:** Could over-boost a line that follows a section header but isn't a title (e.g., a description). Mitigated by the `candidateIndex <= 2` guard and by requiring the candidate to have already passed all hard filters.\n   110→\n   111→---\n   112→\n   113→## Pattern 3: Multi-line split title (1 case)\n   114→\n   115→**Case:** Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables → currently extracts only `LEMON HERB ROASTED`\n   116→\n   117→**Root cause:** The dedup rule \"shorter wins when one is a substring of the other\" kills the 2-line join `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` in favor of the single-line `LEMON HERB ROASTED`. The compound-title protection (`/ [+:&] /`) doesn't match because there's no separator — the second line is just a continuation word.\n   118→\n   119→The caps coalescing logic in `buildCandidates` likely already merges `LEMON HERB RO45TED` + `VEGETABLES` into a single candidate. After OCR repair, both `LEMON HERB ROASTED` (single) and `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` (coalesced or 2-line join) enter the candidate pool. But dedup prefers the shorter one.\n   120→\n   121→**Fix: Protect title continuations from dedup**\n   122→\n   123→In the dedup step, when the longer candidate is a multi-line join (origin `\"2-line\"` or coalesced) and the shorter is its prefix, check if the suffix word(s) are food-related (in `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`). If so, prefer the longer form — it's a complete title, not an accidental substring match.\n   124→\n   125→### Implementation\n   126→\n   127→Modify the dedup filter:\n   128→\n   129→```typescript\n   130→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   131→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   132→  if (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n   133→  return !selected.some((b) => {\n   134→    if (b === a) return false;\n   135→    if (b.text.length >= a.text.length) return false;\n   136→    if (!aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())) return false;\n   137→\n   138→    // NEW: if `a` is a multi-line join and `b` is its prefix,\n   139→    // and the suffix contains a food-related word, keep `a`.\n   140→    if ((a.origin === \"2-line\" || a.origin === \"3-line\") &&\n   141→        aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")) {\n   142→      const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n   143→      const suffixNorm = stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase());\n   144→      if (CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm) ||\n   145→          FOOD_DICTIONARY.has(suffixNorm) ||\n   146→          suffix.split(/\\s+/).some(w => FOOD_DICTIONARY.has(w.toLowerCase()))) {\n   147→        return false; // Don't remove `a` — its suffix is food-related\n   148→      }\n   149→    }\n   150→\n   151→    return true;\n   152→  });\n   153→});\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→**Why this works:** `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` is a 2-line join. Its suffix `VEGETABLES` is in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. The dedup rule now keeps the longer form.\n   157→\n   158→**Risk:** Could keep overly long titles when a food word happens to follow. Mitigated by requiring the longer candidate to be a multi-line join (not a single line that happens to be longer) and by the existing word-count limit (≥8 words already filtered by hard filters).\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Pattern 4: Previous-page content before the title (2 cases)\n   163→\n   164→**Cases:** Mushroom Risotto, Peach Cobbler\n   165→\n   166→**Root cause:** The file starts with instructions/ingredients from the end of a previous recipe. The `findBurstEnd` function's overflow detection looks for explicit markers (`PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW`, `CORRUPTED SECTION`, etc.) but the test cases may not use those exact markers. When the spillover isn't detected, the extractor treats the entire file as one recipe and picks the first \"title-shaped\" line it finds — which may be a different recipe's title embedded in the spillover text, or an instruction line.\n   167→\n   168→The existing `isTitleAbsentPage` check (requires first 3 non-empty lines to be ingredients/instructions/prose) should catch many of these cases. The feedback says it returns `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` for Mushroom Risotto — this is a different recipe's ALL_CAPS title in the spillover. The title-absent guard filters by `rawScore >= 0.10` and `position <= 2`, but the foreign recipe title may be at a low position and have a good rawScore.\n   169→\n   170→**Fix: Extend spillover detection and corroboration**\n   171→\n   172→Two changes:\n   173→\n   174→1. **Broaden `findBurstEnd` to detect implicit spillover:** When the first 3+ non-empty lines are a mix of ingredients, instructions, and body prose (not preceded by any title-shaped line), and then a blank-line gap or visual separator appears, skip past it. This is already partially handled by `isTitleAbsentPage` and the prose-prologue skip in `findBurstEnd`, but the cooking-instruction count threshold is 5 consecutive lines. Lower it to 3 to catch shorter spillover blocks.\n   175→\n   176→2. **Strengthen corroboration for multi-recipe pages:** When multiple ALL_CAPS titles survive to the multi-title guard, and one of them has zero vocabulary overlap with the rest of the document (no content word appears elsewhere), it's from a different recipe. The existing `passesCorroboration` function handles this, but it only runs when `allCapsInScored.length >= 2` in the pre-threshold filter. Ensure it also runs in the multi-title guard's corroboration step, and make the corroboration check consider the **post-spillover** portion of the document only (lines after `findBurstEnd`).\n   177→\n   178→### Implementation\n   179→\n   180→```typescript\n   181→// In findBurstEnd: lower the cooking-instruction prologue threshold\n   182→// from 5 to 3 consecutive lines\n   183→if (j >= 3) {  // was: j >= 5\n   184→  i = j;\n   185→}\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→For the corroboration improvement, modify `passesCorroboration` to accept an optional `startLine` parameter:\n   189→\n   190→```typescript\n   191→function passesCorroboration(\n   192→  text: string,\n   193→  position: number,\n   194→  allLines: string[],\n   195→  startLine: number = 0  // NEW: only check corroboration against lines after this\n   196→): boolean {\n   197→  // ... existing logic, but iterate from startLine instead of 0\n   198→}\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→Then in the multi-title guard, pass `burstEnd` as `startLine` so that vocabulary from the spillover region doesn't count as corroboration for a spillover recipe title.\n   202→\n   203→**Why this works:** `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` has no vocabulary support in the Mushroom Risotto recipe body (no mention of \"carpaccio\", \"pesce\", or \"spada\"). With corroboration checking only the post-spillover region, it gets filtered. `MUSHROOM RISOTTO` (if it appears as a candidate) has vocabulary support (\"mushroom\" in ingredients, \"risotto\" in instructions).\n   204→\n   205→**Risk:** Lowering the instruction-prologue threshold from 5 to 3 could skip legitimate title regions that happen to start with 3 instruction-like lines. Mitigated by the fact that the skip only fires when ALL of the first lines match instruction patterns — a title mixed in would break the streak.\n   206→\n   207→---\n   208→\n   209→## Implementation Order\n   210→\n   211→1. **Pattern 1 (OCR blind repair)** — Highest impact (5 cases). Extract `applyBlindOcrRepair` from `normalizeOcrTitle`, call it in `buildCandidates` for early-position candidates.\n   212→\n   213→2. **Pattern 3 (multi-line dedup fix)** — Simplest change (1 case, dedup rule tweak). Low regression risk.\n   214→\n   215→3. **Pattern 2 (post-header bonus)** — Medium complexity (3 cases). New bonus in scoring pass. Test carefully against existing section-header cases.\n   216→\n   217→4. **Pattern 4 (spillover detection)** — Highest regression risk (2 cases). Changes to `findBurstEnd` and corroboration affect all test cases. Run full eval after each sub-change.\n   218→\n   219→## Testing Strategy\n   220→\n   221→- Run the full eval suite after each pattern fix\n   222→- For each fix, verify that the specific failing cases now pass\n   223→- Watch for regressions in the corresponding pattern category (e.g., OCR repair changes could affect other OCR cases)\n   224→- The eval_only.py script should be used to validate without committing iteration state\n   225→\n   226→## Files to Modify\n   227→\n   228→- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` — all 4 fixes\n   229→- `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts` — possibly add missing food words discovered during Pattern 1 work (only if specific words are needed for dictionary-based repair)\n   230→\n   231→## Open Questions\n   232→\n   233→1. **Pattern 1 scope:** Should blind OCR repair apply to ALL candidates or only the first N lines? First 5 lines is proposed but could be tuned.\n   234→2. **Pattern 2 bonus stacking:** Should the direct-successor bonus stack with the first-after-preamble bonus, or should one subsume the other? Proposed: they stack, but the existing `maxPositionalBoost` cap (0.15) limits the total.\n   235→3. **Pattern 4 threshold:** Is lowering instruction-prologue skip from 5→3 too aggressive? Could try 4 as a middle ground if regressions appear.\n   236→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WX1FwVMG7zLomchYgqNnz2","session_id":"fe3f33e3-f5c0-4e4f-b865-ef8c5a90ce70","uuid":"7bb3d4f2-1dc4-425c-a419-b5287ab25d43"}
