{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ChUVpVurM3QuqCWNb31LMM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 25 → 26 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Title\n     4→\n     5→Fix OCR preamble artifact leaking into compound title assembly\n     6→\n     7→## Status\n     8→\n     9→Draft\n    10→\n    11→## Authors\n    12→\n    13→Claude — 2026-03-17\n    14→\n    15→## Overview\n    16→\n    17→Iteration 25 has 1 real-file failure and 0 generated-file failures. The single failure\n    18→is a compound title where an OCR artifact from a preceding page (`DAT FLATBREADS`) is\n    19→selected instead of the correct second recipe title (`FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`).\n    20→\n    21→The fix introduces **vocabulary corroboration** — a lightweight check that validates\n    22→ALL_CAPS title candidates against the rest of the document before including them in\n    23→multi-title output. This targets the specific failure mode (orphaned OCR artifacts\n    24→masquerading as titles) without disrupting the existing scoring pipeline.\n    25→\n    26→## Background / Problem Statement\n    27→\n    28→### The failure\n    29→\n    30→- **Expected:** `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`\n    31→- **Extracted:** `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n    32→\n    33→The input file contains OCR overflow from a preceding recipe on lines 1–5. Line 4 reads\n    34→`DAT FLATBREADS` — a truncated/corrupted remnant of the previous page's title (likely\n    35→\"OAT FLATBREADS\" or similar). Because it is ALL_CAPS and 2 words, it passes every hard\n    36→filter and looks structurally identical to a real recipe title.\n    37→\n    38→The multi-title logic finds 3 ALL_CAPS candidates (`DAT FLATBREADS`, `FINNISH MILK\n    39→FLATBREADS`, `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`), keeps all 3 (non-first candidates aren't\n    40→sub-headers), caps at 3, and joins them. The extracted result is the first two.\n    41→\n    42→Wait — the extracted output is only 2 titles, not 3. This means either:\n    43→(a) `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` on line 29 was filtered or failed to enter the candidate\n    44→pool (the 25-candidate cap may exclude it), or\n    45→(b) dedup or sub-header logic removed it.\n    46→\n    47→Either way, the root cause is the same: `DAT FLATBREADS` shouldn't be in the pool at all.\n    48→\n    49→### Why existing defenses don't catch it\n    50→\n    51→| Defense | Why it fails |\n    52→|---------|-------------|\n    53→| `findBurstEnd` | Skips garbled lines, but `DAT FLATBREADS` is clean ALL_CAPS — burst detection stops before it |\n    54→| `isLikelyGarbled` | \"DAT\" has vowels, no mixed scripts, no pipes — passes |\n    55→| `passesHardFilters` | 2 words, all-caps, no ingredients/metadata — passes |\n    56→| Embedding scoring | \"DAT FLATBREADS\" embeds close to \"recipe name, dish title\" — decent rawScore |\n    57→| Structural heading | ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words, ≥4 alpha letters each — qualifies |\n    58→\n    59→The extractor has no mechanism to ask: \"Does this candidate's vocabulary appear elsewhere\n    60→in the document?\" For real titles, the answer is almost always yes (the recipe body\n    61→references the dish name, ingredients, or key terms). For orphaned OCR artifacts, the\n    62→answer is typically no.\n    63→\n    64→### What works well (do not change)\n    65→\n    66→- The overall pipeline: candidate generation → hard filters → embedding scoring → multi-title assembly\n    67→- Dictionary-guided OCR repair (iteration 24) — no regressions\n    68→- Compound title dedup protection (iteration 24) — working correctly\n    69→- Bilingual detection and fallback hierarchy — stable\n    70→- Generated file accuracy: 0 failures — the synthetic test suite is fully passing\n    71→\n    72→## Goals\n    73→\n    74→- Fix the 1 real-file failure (FINNISH MILK/POTATO FLATBREADS)\n    75→- Do not regress any currently-passing real or generated files\n    76→- Keep the fix minimal and targeted — the system is 90.9% accurate with 0 generated failures\n    77→\n    78→## Non-Goals\n    79→\n    80→- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n    81→- Reworking the multi-title assembly logic broadly\n    82→- Fixing hypothetical future failure modes not evidenced by current test data\n    83→- Adding new generated test files\n    84→\n    85→---\n    86→\n    87→## Detailed Design\n    88→\n    89→### Root cause analysis\n    90→\n    91→Looking at the actual input file:\n    92→\n    93→```\n    94→Line 1:  \"2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes...\"  ← garbled overflow\n    95→Line 2:  \"nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\"                   ← garbled overflow\n    96→Line 3:  \"3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides...\"                                ← garbled overflow\n    97→Line 4:  \"DAT FLATBREADS\"                                                            ← OCR artifact\n    98→Line 5:  \"le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a...\"                   ← body of previous recipe\n    99→...\n   100→Line 16: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"                                                   ← correct title #1\n   101→...\n   102→Line 29: \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"                                                 ← correct title #2\n   103→```\n   104→\n   105→Lines 1–3 are garbled sentence fragments from the preceding recipe. Despite looking\n   106→garbled, they are **long** (70–200+ characters), so `findBurstEnd`'s short-garbled-line\n   107→skip (which requires `text.length < 20`) does not fire. Lines 1 and 3 start with digits\n   108→(\"2\", \"3\"), so the prose-preamble check (`/^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/`) also does not match them.\n   109→`findBurstEnd` returns 0 — no preamble is detected at all.\n   110→\n   111→Line 4 (`DAT FLATBREADS`) is the tail-end of the previous recipe's title, corrupted by\n   112→OCR. Lines 5+ are the body of that previous recipe. The actual recipes start at line 16.\n   113→\n   114→Because no preamble is skipped, `DAT FLATBREADS` enters the candidate pool as a normal\n   115→ALL_CAPS heading and survives all hard filters.\n   116→\n   117→### Proposed fix: Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title candidates\n   118→\n   119→Add a **corroboration score** to each ALL_CAPS candidate when the multi-title path\n   120→(≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors) is active. The score measures how many of the candidate's\n   121→content words appear elsewhere in the document body.\n   122→\n   123→#### Algorithm\n   124→\n   125→```\n   126→function corroborationScore(candidate, allLines):\n   127→  contentWords = candidate.text\n   128→    .split(/\\s+/)\n   129→    .filter(w => w.length >= 4)       // skip \"THE\", \"WITH\", \"AND\", etc.\n   130→    .map(w => w.toUpperCase())\n   131→\n   132→  if contentWords.length === 0:\n   133→    return 1.0                          // single short word — can't check, pass through\n   134→\n   135→  corroboratedCount = 0\n   136→  for word in contentWords:\n   137→    // Check if word appears in any other line (not the candidate's own line)\n   138→    for line in allLines:\n   139→      if line.position === candidate.position: continue\n   140→      if line.text.toUpperCase().includes(word):\n   141→        corroboratedCount++\n   142→        break\n   143→\n   144→  return corroboratedCount / contentWords.length\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→**Integration point:** In the multi-title assembly block (around line 1254), after\n   148→identifying ≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors but before the sub-header check, filter out candidates\n   149→with corroboration score below a threshold (e.g., 0.5 — meaning fewer than half of the\n   150→candidate's content words appear elsewhere in the document).\n   151→\n   152→#### Why this works for the failure case\n   153→\n   154→| Candidate | Content words | Corroborated? | Score |\n   155→|-----------|--------------|---------------|-------|\n   156→| `DAT FLATBREADS` | DAT, FLATBREADS | DAT: **NO** (appears nowhere else), FLATBREADS: YES (lines 16, 29, etc.) | 0.5 |\n   157→| `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, MILK, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES (lines 29, 5, etc.), MILK: YES (line 21), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n   158→| `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, POTATO, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES, POTATO: YES (line 31, 37), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n   159→\n   160→With a threshold of 0.5 (strict >, not ≥), `DAT FLATBREADS` at exactly 0.5 would be\n   161→removed. With a threshold of `< 0.5` (keep if ≥ 0.5), it would survive.\n   162→\n   163→A safer threshold: require that **all content words of length ≥ 4** are corroborated\n   164→(score = 1.0), OR that the candidate has at least 3 content words with ≥ 2/3 corroborated.\n   165→For 2-word candidates like `DAT FLATBREADS`, this means both words must appear elsewhere.\n   166→\n   167→**Recommended rule:** For candidates with ≤ 3 content words, require 100% corroboration.\n   168→For candidates with > 3 content words, require ≥ 67% corroboration. This is strict for\n   169→short candidates (where a single uncorroborated word is suspicious) and relaxed for long\n   170→ones (where one unusual word in a longer title is acceptable).\n   171→\n   172→```typescript\n   173→const threshold = contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67;\n   174→if (corroborationScore < threshold) {\n   175→  // Remove candidate from multi-title assembly\n   176→}\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→For `DAT FLATBREADS`: 2 content words, threshold = 1.0, score = 0.5 → **removed**.\n   180→\n   181→#### Why this is safe for other cases\n   182→\n   183→- **Single-title pages** (most recipes): Corroboration is only checked in the multi-title\n   184→  path (≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors). Single-title pages are unaffected.\n   185→\n   186→- **Legitimate compound titles** (e.g., `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE`):\n   187→  These are single candidates with compound separators, not multi-title assembly. Unaffected.\n   188→\n   189→- **Multi-recipe pages** where both titles are real: Both titles' content words will appear\n   190→  in their respective recipe bodies (ingredients, descriptions). They corroborate easily.\n   191→\n   192→- **Very short titles** (1 content word, e.g., a hypothetical `GOLONKA`): The\n   193→  `contentWords.length === 0` guard returns 1.0 for candidates with no words ≥ 4 letters.\n   194→  A single 4+ letter word would need corroboration, which is correct — if the word\n   195→  doesn't appear anywhere in the document, it's suspicious.\n   196→\n   197→### Implementation changes\n   198→\n   199→#### File: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   200→\n   201→| Change | Location | Description |\n   202→|--------|----------|-------------|\n   203→| Add `corroborationScore()` function | New function, near scoring helpers | Compute vocabulary overlap between candidate and rest of document |\n   204→| Apply corroboration filter in multi-title path | ~line 1254, inside `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` branch | Remove ALL_CAPS candidates below corroboration threshold before sub-header check |\n   205→\n   206→No new files. No changes to `food-dictionary.ts`, `embeddings.ts`, `findBurstEnd`, or test files.\n   207→\n   208→---\n   209→\n   210→## Testing Strategy\n   211→\n   212→### Verifying the fix\n   213→\n   214→1. **Primary:** Run the title-loop evaluation harness (`tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`)\n   215→   and confirm:\n   216→   - `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` now passes\n   217→   - No regressions in real or generated files\n   218→\n   219→2. **Unit test cases to add** (in `lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts`):\n   220→\n   221→   - **Corroboration rejects orphaned artifact:** Input with garbled preamble + orphaned\n   222→     ALL_CAPS + 2 real recipe titles → only real titles returned\n   223→   - **Corroboration keeps legitimate multi-recipe:** Input with 2 ALL_CAPS titles that\n   224→     both have body text referencing their words → both kept\n   225→\n   226→3. **Edge case tests:**\n   227→   - Short ALL_CAPS title (2 words) where one word is common (\"CHICKEN SOUP\") and appears\n   228→     in body → kept (both words corroborated)\n   229→   - ALL_CAPS title with an unusual/unique word that doesn't appear in body but is\n   230→     clearly the title → still works because it's the only candidate (single-title path,\n   231→     corroboration not applied)\n   232→\n   233→### What not to test\n   234→\n   235→- Generated file generation — 0 failures, don't add new synthetic cases for this pattern\n   236→- Embedding model behavior — not changed\n   237→- OCR repair — not changed\n   238→\n   239→---\n   240→\n   241→## Performance Considerations\n   242→\n   243→The corroboration check iterates over candidate content words × document lines. With\n   244→typical values (2–4 content words, 30–50 lines), this is ~100–200 string operations.\n   245→Negligible compared to the embedding computation (which dominates the 10-second budget).\n   246→\n   247→The `findBurstEnd` improvement adds a constant-time check. No performance impact.\n   248→\n   249→---\n   250→\n   251→## Security Considerations\n   252→\n   253→None. All changes are in local text processing with no I/O or user-facing API changes.\n   254→\n   255→---\n   256→\n   257→## Implementation Phases\n   258→\n   259→### Phase 1: Core fix (single change set)\n   260→\n   261→1. Add `corroborationScore()` helper function\n   262→2. Integrate corroboration filter into multi-title assembly (≥2 ALL_CAPS branch)\n   263→3. Run evaluation harness, confirm fix + no regressions\n   264→\n   265→This is a single-phase change. The fix is small and targeted.\n   266→\n   267→---\n   268→\n   269→## Open Questions\n   270→\n   271→1. **Corroboration threshold for 2-word candidates:** Should we require 100% (both words\n   272→   corroborated) or allow 50% (at least one word)? The 100% rule is safer for the known\n   273→   failure case but could be too strict for hypothetical titles with one unusual word.\n   274→   **Recommendation:** Start with 100% for ≤ 3 content words. If a regression appears,\n   275→   relax to 50%.\n   276→\n   277→2. **Should corroboration apply to single-title path too?** Currently proposed only for\n   278→   multi-title (≥2 ALL_CAPS). Applying it to single-title would add a safety net but\n   279→   risks rejecting legitimate titles with unique words. **Recommendation:** No — the\n   280→   single-title fallback hierarchy already handles this well enough.\n   281→\n   282→3. ~~**Should `findBurstEnd` improvement be included?**~~ Removed — analysis showed that\n   283→   `findBurstEnd` doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not short), so\n   284→   the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire. A preamble detection improvement may be\n   285→   worth pursuing in a future iteration if new failures surface, but it requires a\n   286→   different approach (handling long garbled lines, not just short ones).\n   287→\n   288→---\n   289→\n   290→## References\n   291→\n   292→- Iteration 25 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/feedback.md`\n   293→- Iteration 24 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`\n   294→- Failing test input: `tools/title-loop/input/FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS.real.txt`\n   295→- Multi-title assembly logic: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1245-1314`\n   296→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WX1FwVMG7zLomchYgqNnz2","session_id":"fe3f33e3-f5c0-4e4f-b865-ef8c5a90ce70","uuid":"b4cf2328-3f64-4f3b-b982-081a9e620f3b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MM6YXSFcdomKafFWXdo7JC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 24 → 25 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→18 failures across 7 patterns. The core issue is that the extractor's confidence model is\n     6→too fragile: it rejects plausible title candidates (especially OCR-corrupted ones) without\n     7→a reliable fallback, and its OCR normalization applies digit→letter substitutions without\n     8→considering what letter actually makes sense in context.\n     9→\n    10→The plan addresses failures in three layers:\n    11→1. **Pre-candidate OCR repair** — fix corrupted text *before* candidate scoring, not after\n    12→2. **Category-header bypass** — skip known non-title preamble lines before candidate generation\n    13→3. **Positional confidence floor** — trust the first plausible candidate more aggressively\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter — partial correction (4 failures)\n    18→\n    19→### Root Cause\n    20→\n    21→`normalizeOcrTitle()` runs *after* candidate selection and applies blind substitutions:\n    22→`1→I` in ALL_CAPS, then title-cases the result. But title-casing converts `I` to `i` in\n    23→non-initial positions, producing \"Aruguia\" instead of \"Arugula\". The function doesn't know\n    24→that `1` in \"ARUGU1A\" should become `L` (not `I`), because it has no dictionary or\n    25→context awareness.\n    26→\n    27→The fundamental flaw: **digit→letter mapping is ambiguous without word-level context**.\n    28→`1` can be `I`, `L`, or `l` depending on the word. Post-hoc substitution on the final\n    29→title string can't resolve this ambiguity.\n    30→\n    31→### Proposed Fix: Dictionary-guided OCR repair\n    32→\n    33→Replace the blind `1→I` / `0→O` substitution in `normalizeOcrTitle()` with a\n    34→dictionary-lookup approach:\n    35→\n    36→1. **Build a compact food-word dictionary** (~500 words): common English and Polish recipe\n    37→   words (ingredients, cooking terms, food names). Store lowercase forms.\n    38→   File: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n    39→\n    40→2. **For each word in the title**, enumerate possible digit→letter substitutions\n    41→   (`1→i`, `1→l`, `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, `¡→i`, `Í→i`). Check if any substitution\n    42→   produces a dictionary match. If yes, use that form. If no match, fall back to the\n    43→   current heuristic (positional/case-based).\n    44→\n    45→3. **Apply repair before title-casing**, so the casing step receives clean words.\n    46→\n    47→#### Before / After\n    48→\n    49→```\n    50→Input:  \"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\"\n    51→Before: 1→I → \"BEET ARUGULA SALAD\" → title-case → \"Beet Aruguia Saiad\" ✗\n    52→After:  \"ARUGU1A\" → try \"ARUGULA\" (dict match) ✓ → \"Beet Arugula Salad\" ✓\n    53→\n    54→Input:  \"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"\n    55→Before: 1→I → \"BIACKBERRY FOOI\" → title-case → \"Biackberry Fooi\" ✗\n    56→After:  \"B1ACKBERRY\" → try \"BLACKBERRY\" (dict match) ✓, \"FOO1\" → try \"FOOL\" (dict match) ✓\n    57→\n    58→Input:  \"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\"\n    59→Before: 1→I → \"CHIEB\" → title-case → \"Chieb\" ✗\n    60→After:  \"CH1EB\" → try \"CHLEB\" (dict match) ✓ → \"Chleb Pszenny Razowy\" ✓\n    61→\n    62→Input:  \"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\"\n    63→After:  \"GRILÍED\" → try \"GRILLED\" (dict match) ✓\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→#### Implementation Notes\n    67→\n    68→- Dictionary should be a `Set<string>` of lowercase words, loaded once at module init.\n    69→- For each candidate word, generate all single-digit and multi-digit substitution variants\n    70→  (bounded: max ~8 substitutions per word, max ~256 combinations for 8 digits — but in\n    71→  practice recipe words have 0-2 digit substitutions).\n    72→- To keep it fast, only attempt substitutions when the word contains a known OCR-artifact\n    73→  character (`0-9`, `¡`, `Í`, `€`).\n    74→- The dictionary doesn't need to be exhaustive — it's a positive signal (\"I know this word\"),\n    75→  not a negative one. Unknown words fall through to the existing heuristic.\n    76→\n    77→### Expected Impact\n    78→\n    79→Fixes all 4 Pattern 1 failures. Also improves Pattern 7 (Placki Ziemniaczane) where\n    80→\"SKLADNIK1\" → \"SKŁADNIKI\" would be recognized as a section label rather than noise.\n    81→\n    82→---\n    83→\n    84→## Pattern 2: OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor (5 failures)\n    85→\n    86→### Root Cause\n    87→\n    88→The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation on line 3 is correctly filtered by\n    89→`passesHardFilters`. But the *title line itself* (e.g., \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\")\n    90→contains digits that cause it to be rejected — not by `passesHardFilters` directly,\n    91→but by the embedding scoring. The OCR-corrupted title has poor semantic similarity to\n    92→the \"recipe name\" reference, pushing its rawScore below threshold. The extractor then\n    93→falls through to body text or returns empty.\n    94→\n    95→The secondary issue: `isLikelyGarbled` may reject some corrupted titles because\n    96→digit-interspersed words fail the vowel-ratio check or trigger the \"garbled word\" detector.\n    97→\n    98→### Proposed Fix: Pre-scoring OCR repair on candidates\n    99→\n   100→Apply the dictionary-guided OCR repair (from Pattern 1 fix) **before embedding**, not after.\n   101→This means candidates enter the scoring pipeline as clean text, getting proper embedding\n   102→similarity scores.\n   103→\n   104→Specifically, in `buildCandidates` or at the start of `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`:\n   105→\n   106→1. For each candidate text, apply the dictionary-guided repair function.\n   107→2. Store both the original text (for position tracking) and the repaired text (for embedding).\n   108→3. Embed the **repaired** text. Return the **repaired** text as the result.\n   109→\n   110→This also helps `isLikelyGarbled` and `passesHardFilters`: repair the text before\n   111→running filters, so \"1ngredients\" becomes \"Ingredients\" (→ section label → filtered),\n   112→and \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" becomes \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" (→ passes\n   113→all filters, embeds well).\n   114→\n   115→#### Before / After\n   116→\n   117→```\n   118→Input line: \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"\n   119→Before: Poor embedding → rawScore below threshold → empty result\n   120→After:  Repaired to \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" → strong embedding → selected ✓\n   121→\n   122→Input line: \"Drożdże Sern1k\"\n   123→Before: \"Sern1k\" → poor embedding → falls to body text\n   124→After:  Repaired to \"Drożdże Sernik\" → strong embedding → selected ✓\n   125→```\n   126→\n   127→### Expected Impact\n   128→\n   129→Fixes all 5 Pattern 2 failures. Also indirectly helps Pattern 7.\n   130→\n   131→---\n   132→\n   133→## Pattern 3: Category/section header precedes the actual title (3 failures)\n   134→\n   135→### Root Cause\n   136→\n   137→The three cases have different preamble styles:\n   138→\n   139→1. **\"FISH & SEAFOOD\"** — already in `SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. But the real title\n   140→   \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" (mixed-case, position 2) competes poorly because\n   141→   the structural heading logic finds no ALL_CAPS heading to anchor on. The extractor\n   142→   falls through to body text.\n   143→\n   144→2. **\"VEGETABLES\"** — already in `SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. Same scoring problem.\n   145→\n   146→3. **\"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\"** — filtered by `\" | \"` check. But then\n   147→   \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" at position 2 should be found as an ALL_CAPS candidate.\n   148→\n   149→For cases 1 and 2, the issue is that after the category header is filtered, the\n   150→mixed-case title at position 2 doesn't score high enough. There's no \"first non-filtered\n   151→candidate gets a position boost\" logic — the position factor only rewards position 0 in\n   152→the raw line array, not position 0 among surviving candidates.\n   153→\n   154→For case 3 (Ogórkowa Zupa returning empty), the pipe-delimited metadata line is at\n   155→position 0, and \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" is at position 2. The metadata line consumes line 0,\n   156→and there's likely a failure in `findBurstEnd` to skip it — or the ALL_CAPS title\n   157→at position 2 isn't getting enough structural heading bonus because position 0 is gone.\n   158→\n   159→### Proposed Fix: Candidate-relative position bonus\n   160→\n   161→Change the position factor calculation from raw line position to **candidate-relative\n   162→position** — i.e., position among candidates that passed hard filters:\n   163→\n   164→```typescript\n   165→// Current: position in raw lines\n   166→const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   167→\n   168→// Proposed: position among surviving candidates (0.0 for first candidate)\n   169→const candidateIndex = candidates.findIndex(c => c.text === rs.text);\n   170→const candidateRelativePosition = candidateIndex / candidates.length;\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→This way, when \"FISH & SEAFOOD\" is filtered, \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" becomes\n   174→the first surviving candidate and gets the maximum position bonus.\n   175→\n   176→Additionally, add a **\"first candidate after filtered preamble\" bonus**: when the first\n   177→N lines are all filtered (section labels, metadata, page refs), the first surviving\n   178→candidate should get an explicit bonus (e.g., +0.08) because it occupies the structural\n   179→\"title position\" in the document.\n   180→\n   181→#### Before / After\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→\"FISH & SEAFOOD\" (filtered) / \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" (position 2)\n   185→Before: position factor = 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - 2/50*2) = ~1.11 — modest boost\n   186→After:  first-surviving-candidate bonus = +0.08, candidateRelativePosition = 0.0\n   187→\n   188→\"Lato | Zupy | ...\" (filtered) / \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\" (position 2)\n   189→Before: structural heading bonus applies but threshold may be too high\n   190→After:  first-surviving-candidate bonus ensures it clears threshold\n   191→```\n   192→\n   193→### Expected Impact\n   194→\n   195→Fixes all 3 Pattern 3 failures.\n   196→\n   197→---\n   198→\n   199→## Pattern 4: Title absent from captured text (2 failures)\n   200→\n   201→### Root Cause\n   202→\n   203→When the OCR capture starts mid-recipe (no title present), the extractor should ideally\n   204→return empty. Instead:\n   205→\n   206→- **Mushroom Risotto**: picks up \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n   207→  — the title of the *next* recipe in the same file. These are ALL_CAPS structural headings\n   208→  that score well.\n   209→\n   210→- **Sweet Potato Salad**: picks up \"Salt and pepper\" — a short phrase that passes hard filters.\n   211→\n   212→### Proposed Fix: Detect title-absent pages\n   213→\n   214→Add a \"no-title confidence check\": when the best candidate's rawScore is below a minimum\n   215→absolute threshold (e.g., 0.05) AND the candidate is not in the first 3 non-empty lines,\n   216→return empty rather than guessing.\n   217→\n   218→More specifically:\n   219→1. If the file starts with ingredient-like lines or cooking instructions (detected by\n   220→   `looksLikeIngredient` or `looksLikeCookingInstruction` on the first 3 non-empty lines),\n   221→   flag the page as \"title-absent candidate\".\n   222→2. In this mode, require a higher rawScore threshold (e.g., 0.10) for any candidate to\n   223→   be accepted.\n   224→3. For the Mushroom Risotto case: the best candidate (\"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA...\") is\n   225→   at position 4 (deep in the file after body text) and the file starts with body text —\n   226→   the title-absent detection should prevent selection.\n   227→\n   228→#### Before / After\n   229→\n   230→```\n   231→Mushroom Risotto: starts with \"Reduce heat and stir...\"\n   232→Before: selects \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n   233→After:  first 3 lines are cooking instructions → title-absent mode → returns empty ✓\n   234→\n   235→Sweet Potato Salad: starts with \"2 large sweet potatoes...\"\n   236→Before: selects \"Salt and pepper\"\n   237→After:  first 3 lines are ingredients → title-absent mode → returns empty ✓\n   238→```\n   239→\n   240→### Expected Impact\n   241→\n   242→Fixes both Pattern 4 failures. Returning empty is the correct behavior when no title\n   243→exists in the captured text.\n   244→\n   245→---\n   246→\n   247→## Pattern 5: Compound title — only variation extracted (2 failures)\n   248→\n   249→### Root Cause\n   250→\n   251→The compound title \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   252→is on line 1. It should pass hard filters (the ` : ` exception for colon-terminated lines\n   253→exists at line 306). But the extractor returns \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\",\n   254→which looks like a section header from later in the file.\n   255→\n   256→Looking at the file: line 1 has the compound title, line 3 has \"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED\n   257→PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\". The issue is that line 1 has 10 words — exceeding the 8-word limit\n   258→in `passesHardFilters` (line 324). The exception `/ [+:&/] /` is checked, but ` : ` in\n   259→this title means `+` and `&` don't match. Let me re-read... the regex is `/ [+:&/] /` —\n   260→that's a character class `[+:&/]`, so `:` IS included. So the 8-word filter should be\n   261→bypassed.\n   262→\n   263→Wait — counting: \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   264→= \"HERB\", \"ROASTED\", \"PORK\", \"WITH\", \"MUSHROOMS\", \":\", \"PORK\", \"WITH\", \"CARAMELIZED\",\n   265→\"ONIONS\", \"(VARIATION)\" = 11 words. The check is `words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)`.\n   266→The text contains \" : \" so the exception fires — this should pass.\n   267→\n   268→But wait, the `stripParentheticalGloss` function strips \"(VARIATION)\" because the base\n   269→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\" is ALL_CAPS and\n   270→\"VARIATION\" is ALL_CAPS → the function keeps it (line 397: `if (isAllCaps(paren)) return text`).\n   271→So the full title should survive.\n   272→\n   273→The most likely cause: the line is > 80 characters. Let me count:\n   274→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\" = 77 chars.\n   275→Under 80, so it passes the length check.\n   276→\n   277→Re-examining: the feedback says the extractor returns \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\".\n   278→The `--` prefix suggests this comes from a line deeper in the file that starts with `--`.\n   279→Let me look at the actual file content more carefully.\n   280→\n   281→Actually, looking at the file again — line 1 *does* pass hard filters, so it enters the\n   282→candidate pool. The issue must be in the scoring/dedup phase. The line 3 candidate\n   283→\"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" ends with no colon issue... wait, it\n   284→ends without `:` at the end. But \"MAIN RECIPE:\" at the start — does this get filtered?\n   285→No, it's not a section label or metadata pattern.\n   286→\n   287→The dedup logic (line 1044): \"if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter one.\"\n   288→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" (from line 3, after stripping \"MAIN RECIPE: \") may\n   289→be a substring of the compound title. The dedup would keep the shorter one, destroying\n   290→the compound title.\n   291→\n   292→**This is the real bug**: the \"shorter wins\" dedup rule is designed to prevent\n   293→\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" from beating \"Pierogi Ruskie\", but it also causes\n   294→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" to beat the full compound title.\n   295→\n   296→For the PIERNIK case: \"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\" on line 1,\n   297→and likely \"WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\" or similar from a later section header.\n   298→The `+` exception in the 8-word filter should let the compound title through. But\n   299→if a sub-section header like \"PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\" appears later and is\n   300→a substring of the compound title, dedup kills the compound title.\n   301→\n   302→### Proposed Fix: Protect compound titles from substring dedup\n   303→\n   304→Add compound-title protection to the dedup step: when a candidate contains ` : ` or ` + `\n   305→(compound separator), it should not be removed by shorter-substring dedup. The compound\n   306→form is the intended complete title.\n   307→\n   308→```typescript\n   309→// In the dedup filter, skip removal if the longer candidate is a compound title\n   310→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   311→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   312→  // Protect compound titles from substring dedup\n   313→  if (/ [+:] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n   314→  return !selected.some(\n   315→    (b) =>\n   316→      b !== a &&\n   317→      aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n   318→      b.text.length < a.text.length\n   319→  );\n   320→});\n   321→```\n   322→\n   323→Also, add \"MAIN RECIPE\" to the filtered prefixes or metadata patterns so\n   324→\"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" doesn't enter the candidate pool\n   325→as a competitor. Pattern: `/^MAIN\\s+RECIPE\\s*:/i`.\n   326→\n   327→Similarly, lines starting with `--` followed by a section label (like \"--VARIATION:\",\n   328→\"--WERSJA\") should be filtered as structural sub-headers.\n   329→\n   330→#### Before / After\n   331→\n   332→```\n   333→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   334→Before: dedup removes it in favor of shorter substring → falls to \"--VARIATION: ...\"\n   335→After:  compound title protected from dedup → returned as-is ✓\n   336→\n   337→\"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   338→Before: dedup removes in favor of shorter substring → \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   339→After:  compound title protected → returned as-is ✓\n   340→```\n   341→\n   342→### Expected Impact\n   343→\n   344→Fixes both Pattern 5 failures.\n   345→\n   346→---\n   347→\n   348→## Pattern 6: Polish title + English subtitle on line 2 (1 failure)\n   349→\n   350→### Root Cause\n   351→\n   352→\"Golonka\" (single word, mixed-case) at position 0, \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" at position 1.\n   353→The extractor returns cooking instruction text from deep in the file.\n   354→\n   355→The `pos0Primary` subtitle suppression logic (line 891) fires when position-0 candidate\n   356→has ≤5 words and is followed by a longer mixed-case candidate. But the penalty (-0.15)\n   357→is applied to the *subtitle*, not to help the title. The real problem is that \"Golonka\"\n   358→itself scores poorly on embeddings (single Polish food word vs. English reference\n   359→\"recipe name, dish title\") and falls below threshold.\n   360→\n   361→The fallback logic (line 915-925) should catch this: when all candidates are below\n   362→threshold, it picks the earliest with rawScore > -0.05 for position ≤ 2. But \"Golonka\"\n   363→might not be the earliest candidate if it was somehow filtered or if \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\"\n   364→at position 1 has a better score.\n   365→\n   366→Actually, looking more carefully: \"Golonka\" should pass all hard filters and become\n   367→position-0 candidate. The fallback should pick it. The fact that the extractor returns\n   368→\"Scatter vegetables around pan. + Sauce: Remove knuckles...\" suggests something deeper\n   369→is wrong — possibly \"Scatter vegetables around pan.\" passes hard filters (it's a cooking\n   370→instruction but wordCount is only 4, and `looksLikeCookingInstruction` checks for ≥4 words\n   371→AND starts with cooking verb — \"Scatter\" is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`!).\n   372→\n   373→**Secondary bug**: \"Scatter\" (and several other cooking verbs) are missing from\n   374→`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`.\n   375→\n   376→### Proposed Fix: Two changes\n   377→\n   378→1. **Expand `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`** to include missing verbs: \"scatter\", \"score\",\n   379→   \"pat\", \"rub\", \"pour\", \"skim\", \"strain\", \"heat\", \"discard\", \"rest\", \"marinate\", \"wrap\".\n   380→\n   381→2. **Strengthen position-0 single-word title handling**: When position 0 has a single\n   382→   word that passed hard filters and position 1 has a plausible subtitle (2-5 words,\n   383→   mixed-case, not ingredients), treat position 0 as a high-confidence title candidate\n   384→   regardless of embedding score. This is a structural pattern: `[FoodName]\\n[English Translation]\\n\\nIngredients:` is a standard bilingual recipe layout.\n   385→\n   386→   Specifically: if the first candidate is at position 0 with 1-2 words, and position 1\n   387→   has a mixed-case line of 2-5 words that is NOT an ingredient or instruction, AND\n   388→   position 2+ starts with \"Ingredients:\" or similar section label, boost the position-0\n   389→   candidate by +0.15 (enough to clear any threshold).\n   390→\n   391→#### Before / After\n   392→\n   393→```\n   394→\"Golonka\" (pos 0) / \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" (pos 1) / \"Ingredients:\" (pos 3)\n   395→Before: \"Golonka\" has weak embedding → falls below threshold → body text selected\n   396→After:  bilingual pattern detected → \"Golonka\" boosted → selected ✓\n   397→```\n   398→\n   399→### Expected Impact\n   400→\n   401→Fixes Pattern 6. The cooking-verb expansion also helps prevent future body-text leakage.\n   402→\n   403→---\n   404→\n   405→## Pattern 7: Heavy OCR corruption in body, clean title skipped (1 failure)\n   406→\n   407→### Root Cause\n   408→\n   409→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" is clean ALL_CAPS on line 1. The body is extremely corrupted with\n   410→Cyrillic characters, pipe symbols, and digit substitutions. The extractor returns\n   411→\"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\" — a corrupted instruction line.\n   412→\n   413→The title should be found: it's ALL_CAPS, 2 words, at position 0. The structural heading\n   414→logic should identify it. But the body corruption may produce false-positive candidates\n   415→that score higher, or the heavy corruption may confuse `findBurstEnd`.\n   416→\n   417→Most likely: \"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" is correctly identified as a structural heading and\n   418→gets the +0.10 bonus. But \"SKLADNIK1:\" on line 3 looks like a section label after\n   419→OCR repair (SKŁADNIKI → section label). The instruction lines with Cyrillic text may\n   420→bypass `isLikelyGarbled` because they contain enough vowels in the Cyrillic portions.\n   421→\n   422→Actually, the simplest explanation: \"Sp|aszcz\" passes hard filters because `|` is not\n   423→explicitly filtered (only `\" | \"` with spaces is filtered). And the mixed Cyrillic/Latin\n   424→text has enough vowels to pass the garbled check.\n   425→\n   426→### Proposed Fix: Strengthen garbled-text detection\n   427→\n   428→1. **Filter pipe characters in words**: A word containing `|` (pipe) within letter\n   429→   sequences is OCR noise. Add to `isLikelyGarbled`: if any word contains `|` between\n   430→   letters, mark as garbled.\n   431→\n   432→2. **Filter mixed-script text**: If a line contains both Latin and Cyrillic characters,\n   433→   it's OCR corruption. Add: `if (/[а-яА-Я]/.test(text) && /[a-zA-Z]/.test(text)) return true;`\n   434→\n   435→3. **With the pre-scoring OCR repair** (from Pattern 1/2 fix), \"SKLADNIK1\" becomes\n   436→   \"SKŁADNIKI\" → recognized as section label → filtered. This removes a false positive\n   437→   that may have been competing with the real title.\n   438→\n   439→#### Before / After\n   440→\n   441→```\n   442→\"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\"\n   443→Before: passes isLikelyGarbled (enough vowels), passes passesHardFilters\n   444→After:  pipe-in-word check → garbled → filtered out\n   445→\n   446→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\" (line 1, clean ALL_CAPS)\n   447→Before: competes with corrupted body text → loses\n   448→After:  corrupted body text all filtered → wins easily ✓\n   449→```\n   450→\n   451→### Expected Impact\n   452→\n   453→Fixes Pattern 7. Also improves robustness on any future files with OCR mixing scripts.\n   454→\n   455→---\n   456→\n   457→## Summary of Changes\n   458→\n   459→### New file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   460→\n   461→A `Set<string>` of ~500 common English and Polish food/cooking words used for\n   462→dictionary-guided OCR repair. Words are stored lowercase, without diacritics (for\n   463→OCR-resilient matching).\n   464→\n   465→### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   466→\n   467→| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n   468→|--------|----------|----------------|\n   469→| Dictionary-guided OCR repair function | New function `repairOcrWord()` | 1, 2, 7 |\n   470→| Apply OCR repair before candidate scoring | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, before embed calls | 1, 2, 7 |\n   471→| Candidate-relative position bonus | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, position factor calc | 3 |\n   472→| First-after-preamble bonus | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, after buildCandidates | 3 |\n   473→| Title-absent page detection | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, early return | 4 |\n   474→| Protect compound titles from dedup | Dedup filter block | 5 |\n   475→| Filter \"MAIN RECIPE:\" prefix | `METADATA_PATTERNS` | 5 |\n   476→| Filter `--VARIATION:` sub-headers | `passesHardFilters` | 5 |\n   477→| Expand cooking verb list | `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` | 6 |\n   478→| Bilingual layout pattern boost | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, new bonus | 6 |\n   479→| Pipe-in-word garbled detection | `isLikelyGarbled` | 7 |\n   480→| Mixed Cyrillic/Latin garbled detection | `isLikelyGarbled` | 7 |\n   481→\n   482→### Expected accuracy impact\n   483→\n   484→| Pattern | Count | Expected Fix Rate |\n   485→|---------|-------|-------------------|\n   486→| 1. OCR digits, partial correction | 4 | 4/4 (dictionary repair) |\n   487→| 2. OCR annotation confuses extractor | 5 | 5/5 (pre-scoring repair) |\n   488→| 3. Category header before title | 3 | 3/3 (candidate-relative position) |\n   489→| 4. Title absent from text | 2 | 2/2 (title-absent detection) |\n   490→| 5. Compound title truncated | 2 | 2/2 (dedup protection) |\n   491→| 6. Subtitle on line 2 | 1 | 1/1 (bilingual boost + verb expansion) |\n   492→| 7. Heavy body corruption | 1 | 1/1 (garbled detection + OCR repair) |\n   493→| **Total** | **18** | **18/18** |\n   494→\n   495→### Risk Assessment\n   496→\n   497→- **Dictionary-guided OCR repair** is the highest-risk change (new code path, could\n   498→  over-correct clean text). Mitigation: only trigger when word contains a known\n   499→  OCR-artifact character; dictionary match is a positive signal, not a filter.\n   500→\n   501→- **Compound title dedup protection** could allow over-long titles to survive. Mitigation:\n   502→  only protects titles with explicit ` : ` or ` + ` separators, which are intentional\n   503→  compound forms.\n   504→\n   505→- **Title-absent detection** could produce false negatives (return empty when title exists\n   506→  but is preceded by ingredient-like lines). Mitigation: only trigger when the *first 3*\n   507→  non-empty lines are all ingredients/instructions — rare for files that do have a title.\n   508→\n   509→- **Candidate-relative position bonus** changes scoring for all files, not just the 3\n   510→  failures. Mitigation: the bonus is additive to existing position factor, not a replacement.\n   511→  Files where position-0 candidate is correct (the common case) are unaffected because\n   512→  their first candidate is also position-0 in the raw array.\n   513→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WX1FwVMG7zLomchYgqNnz2","session_id":"fe3f33e3-f5c0-4e4f-b865-ef8c5a90ce70","uuid":"05a40243-55f5-4234-9254-15230171f8c7"}
