{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WX1FwVMG7zLomchYgqNnz2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent. I now have comprehensive improvement plans from iterations 20-26. The document I read initially is iteration 27's improvement plan (which is actually a draft for iteration 28). Let me analyze this for contradictions systematically.\n\n## CONTRADICTION ANALYSIS: Iteration 27/28 Plan vs. Previous Iterations\n\nBased on my review of improvement plans from iterations 20-26, I found **3 significant tensions/contradictions** and **1 prior-work interaction** in the iteration 27/28 plan:\n\n---\n\n### **CONTRADICTION 1: OCR Blind Repair Logic (Pattern 1)**\n\n**Current Plan (Iteration 27/28):**\n- Applies blind digit→letter substitution **BEFORE embedding** for candidates in first 5 lines\n- Extracts logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` into reusable `applyBlindOcrRepair` \n- Generates additional \"OCR-repaired\" candidate variants during candidate building\n\n**Previous Contradictory Work:**\n\n**Iteration 24** (lines 30-65) introduced **dictionary-guided OCR repair** as a pre-scoring fix:\n- Enumerates digit→letter substitutions and checks against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n- Applies repair before embedding for ALL candidates\n- States: \"Apply repair before title-casing\"\n- Risk mitigated by \"dictionary match is positive signal\"\n\n**Iteration 26** (lines 75-119) **expanded OCR repair dictionary** instead of changing the mechanism:\n- Added `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` (~50 words) to cover \"with\", \"dip\", \"the\", etc.\n- States explicitly: \"Merge this into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (or check both sets)\"\n- Approach: make **dictionary repair more complete**, not replace it\n\n**The Contradiction:**\n- **Iteration 24-26 approach:** Repair all candidates dictionary-guided, fix by expanding dictionary\n- **Iteration 27/28 approach:** Abandon dictionary approach, apply **blind substitution** to first 5 lines only\n- This represents a **strategic reversal** — going from dictionary-aware to blind substitution\n- Iteration 27/28 acknowledges the 5 OCR failures but proposes a completely different mechanism than what iteration 26 just proposed\n\n**Does Iteration 27/28 acknowledge this?**\n- No explicit acknowledgment of the strategic shift from dictionary-guided to blind repair\n- No mention of why blind repair is superior to expanding the dictionary further\n- The plan treats this as a new issue despite iteration 26 directly addressing the same failures\n\n**Assessment:** This is a **moderate contradiction**. The iteration 27/28 plan should explain why blind substitution (with all its risks) is preferred over dictionary expansion, especially since iteration 26 already took a step in that direction.\n\n---\n\n### **CONTRADICTION 2: First-After-Preamble Bonus Stacking (Pattern 2)**\n\n**Current Plan (Iteration 27/28):**\n- Adds new \"direct-successor bonus\" of +0.10 when previous line is section header/metadata\n- States: \"both bonuses fire, cap combined at +0.15\" (Open Questions #2)\n- Implementation creates TWO bonuses:\n  1. Existing `first-after-preamble` (+0.08 to +0.12)\n  2. New `direct-successor` (+0.10)\n\n**Previous Work:**\n\n**Iteration 24** (lines 159-191) introduced `first-after-preamble` bonus:\n- +0.08 to +0.12 bonus when all preceding lines filtered\n- Includes: \"When both bonuses fire for the same candidate, cap combined at +0.15\"\n- States it was designed to handle cases like \"FISH & SEAFOOD\" header → real title\n\n**Iteration 26** (lines 206-252) **strengthened the existing first-after-preamble bonus**:\n- Increased from +0.08 to +0.12 specifically for section-label preambles\n- Added `isSectionLabel` check to robust bonus detection\n- Explicitly caps combined positional boost at +0.15: \"if both bonuses fire for the same candidate, the combined positional boost could reach ~+0.24. To prevent over-boosting: cap at +0.15\"\n\n**The Contradiction:**\n- **Iteration 26 approach:** Strengthen the existing first-after-preamble bonus and rely on the +0.15 cap\n- **Iteration 27/28 approach:** Add a SECOND bonus (direct-successor) at +0.10, with same cap\n- This creates **layering complexity**: two separate bonus mechanisms for what iteration 26 treated as a single strengthened bonus\n- The \"direct-successor\" bonus fires on a stricter condition (immediately preceding line only), which is a narrower scope than first-after-preamble (all preceding lines)\n\n**Does Iteration 27/28 acknowledge this?**\n- No mention of iteration 26's approach or why that wasn't sufficient\n- The plan treats this as a new insight (\"extend the bonus to fire when the *immediately preceding* line\") but iteration 26 already had the first-after-preamble mechanism\n\n**Assessment:** This is a **moderate contradiction**. Iteration 27/28 proposes a new bonus when iteration 26 just strengthened the existing one. The plans should be reconciled — either the stronger existing bonus is insufficient (and needs new direct-successor), or iteration 26's approach handles the cases already.\n\n---\n\n### **CONTRADICTION 3: findBurstEnd Threshold Change (Pattern 4)**\n\n**Current Plan (Iteration 27/28):**\n- Lower cooking-instruction prologue threshold from 5→3 consecutive lines (line 183)\n- States: \"skip past [spillover] when... a blank-line gap... separator... ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words\"\n- Claims: \"lowering from 5→3 is not too aggressive\" because instruction-line matching is strict\n\n**Previous Work:**\n\n**Iteration 21** (lines 101-116) introduced prose-prologue detection:\n```typescript\nif (j >= 3) i = j;  // Lower threshold than cooking instructions (3 vs 5)\n```\n- Explicitly chose 3 for **prose** lines to catch shorter spillover blocks\n- But this was for **body prose** detection (lowercase starts, 5+ words), NOT for cooking instructions\n- The existing cooking-instruction detection already had threshold 5\n\n**Iteration 26** (lines 164-204) improved spillover handling:\n- States: \"skip ALL subsequent lines until either (a) ≥2 blank lines, (b) separator, (c) ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words\"\n- Does NOT change the cooking-instruction threshold from 5\n- Proposes expanding the skip logic to detect separators more aggressively\n\n**The Tension:**\n- **Iteration 21-26 approach:** Use threshold 5 for cooking instructions, threshold 3 for prose\n- **Iteration 27/28 approach:** Lower cooking-instruction threshold to 3\n- Iteration 26 **did not** recommend lowering the instruction threshold; it recommended improving separator detection\n- The iteration 27/28 plan says \"lowering from 5→3 won't cause false positives\" but this contradicts the original design rationale from iteration 21 (choosing 5 to avoid skipping legitimate titles)\n\n**Does Iteration 27/28 acknowledge this?**\n- No acknowledgment of iteration 21-26's reasoning\n- No justification for why the \"strict instruction matching\" claim now makes threshold 3 safe\n- States \"Risk: lowering could skip legitimate title regions that start with 3 instruction-like lines\" but doesn't explain why this risk is now acceptable after iteration 21's caution\n\n**Assessment:** This is a **moderate contradiction**. The iteration should explain why the threshold can now safely drop to 3 when previous iterations used 5 precisely because 3 was too aggressive.\n\n---\n\n### **CROSS-ITERATION INTERACTION: Multi-line Dedup Fix (Pattern 3)**\n\n**Current Plan (Iteration 27/28, Pattern 3):**\n- Protects multi-line joins from dedup when suffix contains food-related words\n- Checks: `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` and `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n\n**Related Prior Work (not a direct contradiction, but important context):**\n\n**Iteration 24** (lines 302-340) introduced **compound-title dedup protection**:\n- Protects titles with ` : ` or ` + ` separators from substring dedup\n- States: \"the shorter wins dedup rule is designed to prevent accidental substring matches\"\n\n**Iteration 22** (lines 249-278) **removed compound-variant stripping**:\n- Stopped trimming compound titles to keep full form\n- This was to preserve full compound titles like `LEMON CURD : LEMON CURD WITH THYME`\n\n**The Interaction:**\n- **Iteration 24-22 logic:** Protect compound titles (with explicit separators) from dedup\n- **Iteration 27/28 logic:** Protect multi-line joins (without separators) from dedup based on suffix food words\n- These are **complementary**, not contradictory, but the current plan should acknowledge iteration 24's existing dedup protection\n- The \"shorter wins\" rule is still in effect; iteration 27/28 adds a food-word override\n\n**Does Iteration 27/28 acknowledge this?**\n- No mention of iteration 24's compound-title protection\n- Plan treats this as a new dedup fix without acknowledging the prior architecture\n\n**Assessment:** This is **not a contradiction** but an important **integration point**. The implementation should work with iteration 24's existing compound-title protection, not duplicate or override it.\n\n---\n\n### **SUMMARY TABLE**\n\n| # | Topic | Iteration 27/28 Approach | Previous Iterations | Contradiction Severity | Acknowledgment |\n|---|-------|--------------------------|---------------------|----------------------|-----------------|\n| 1 | OCR Repair Mechanism | Blind digit→letter substitution before embedding | Iteration 24-26: Dictionary-guided repair + expand dictionary | **Moderate** | None |\n| 2 | First-After-Preamble Bonus | Add new direct-successor bonus | Iteration 26: Strengthen existing bonus to +0.12 + cap | **Moderate** | None |\n| 3 | findBurstEnd Threshold | Lower cooking-instruction from 5→3 | Iteration 21-26: Keep at 5, improve separator detection | **Moderate** | None |\n| 4 | Multi-line Dedup Protection | Protect joins with food-word suffix | Iteration 24: Protect compound titles with separators | None (complementary) | None |\n\n---\n\n### **RECOMMENDATIONS**\n\n1. **For Pattern 1:** Clarify why blind repair is superior to dictionary expansion. Consider if a hybrid approach (dictionary-guided for mid-file candidates + blind for first 5 lines) would be better.\n\n2. **For Pattern 2:** Verify iteration 26's strengthened first-after-preamble bonus isn't already sufficient for the 3 failing cases. If not, explain why the direct-successor bonus is needed as an addition.\n\n3. **For Pattern 4:** Re-evaluate the threshold choice. If iteration 21's reasoning (5 is safer) is still valid, keep it. If new context makes 3 safe, explain the changed assumptions.\n\n4. **For Pattern 3:** Integrate explicitly with iteration 24's existing compound-title dedup protection to avoid duplication or conflicts."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ad2583e575cc4e5f6 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 132884\ntool_uses: 11\nduration_ms: 51450</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe3f33e3-f5c0-4e4f-b865-ef8c5a90ce70","uuid":"c2403fe5-e175-487b-ba60-b6b4985a29f5","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to check for contradictions between the current improvement plan (iteration 27, at tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md) and all previous iteration plans.\n\nThe current plan proposes 4 changes:\n1. **OCR blind repair**: Apply blind digit→letter substitution BEFORE embedding for first 5 lines (extracted from normalizeOcrTitle)\n2. **Post-header bonus**: +0.10 direct-successor bonus when previous line is a section header/metadata\n3. **Multi-line dedup fix**: Protect multi-line joins from dedup when suffix contains food-related words\n4. **Spillover detection**: Lower findBurstEnd cooking-instruction threshold from 5→3, pass startLine to passesCorroboration\n\nPlease read the improvement plans from the most relevant recent iterations. Focus on iterations 20-26 first, then check earlier ones if needed. Search specifically for:\n- Any previous changes to OCR repair logic, normalizeOcrTitle, or blind substitution\n- Any previous changes to positional bonuses, first-after-preamble, or section header handling\n- Any previous changes to dedup rules, substring filtering, or multi-line join handling\n- Any previous changes to findBurstEnd, spillover detection, instruction-prologue thresholds, or passesCorroboration\n- Any previous threshold changes that might conflict (e.g., instruction count thresholds, bonus amounts, line position limits)\n\nFor each potential contradiction found, report:\n- Which iteration made the original change\n- What the original change was and why\n- How the current plan contradicts it\n- Whether the current plan acknowledges this\n\nBe thorough - read all plans from iteration 20 onward, and selectively check earlier ones for the specific topics above.","agentId":"ad2583e575cc4e5f6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent. I now have comprehensive improvement plans from iterations 20-26. The document I read initially is iteration 27's improvement plan (which is actually a draft for iteration 28). Let me analyze this for contradictions systematically.\n\n## CONTRADICTION ANALYSIS: Iteration 27/28 Plan vs. Previous Iterations\n\nBased on my review of improvement plans from iterations 20-26, I found **3 significant tensions/contradictions** and **1 prior-work interaction** in the iteration 27/28 plan:\n\n---\n\n### **CONTRADICTION 1: OCR Blind Repair Logic (Pattern 1)**\n\n**Current Plan (Iteration 27/28):**\n- Applies blind digit→letter substitution **BEFORE embedding** for candidates in first 5 lines\n- Extracts logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` into reusable `applyBlindOcrRepair` \n- Generates additional \"OCR-repaired\" candidate variants during candidate building\n\n**Previous Contradictory Work:**\n\n**Iteration 24** (lines 30-65) introduced **dictionary-guided OCR repair** as a pre-scoring fix:\n- Enumerates digit→letter substitutions and checks against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n- Applies repair before embedding for ALL candidates\n- States: \"Apply repair before title-casing\"\n- Ris