{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019qnL8ZhPhERnxmo4ZsF18i","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 26 → 27 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Title\n     4→\n     5→Fix generated-file title extraction: OCR repair gaps, section-label merge blocking, and spillover handling\n     6→\n     7→## Status\n     8→\n     9→Draft\n    10→\n    11→## Authors\n    12→\n    13→Claude — 2026-03-17\n    14→\n    15→## Overview\n    16→\n    17→Iteration 26 has 0 real-file failures and 16 generated-file failures across 6 patterns.\n    18→Real accuracy is 100% (11/11). Combined accuracy is 85.6%.\n    19→\n    20→The failures share two root causes:\n    21→\n    22→1. **OCR repair has blind spots** — the food dictionary lacks common English words\n    23→   (`with`, `the`, `and`, `dip`, `pie`), so `repairOcrWord` can't fix them. Partially-\n    24→   repaired titles like `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` score poorly on embeddings and\n    25→   get skipped.\n    26→\n    27→2. **Structural heuristics are too rigid** — section labels block multi-line title\n    28→   merges even when the label is clearly a title continuation; spillover markers don't\n    29→   trigger a wider scan; and mid-recipe pages aren't reliably detected when body text\n    30→   precedes ingredients.\n    31→\n    32→The fix addresses both causes with targeted changes: expand the OCR repair dictionary,\n    33→relax section-label merge blocking for title continuations, and improve spillover/\n    34→mid-recipe detection. The pipeline architecture is unchanged.\n    35→\n    36→## Background / Problem Statement\n    37→\n    38→### Failure breakdown\n    39→\n    40→| Pattern | Count | Returns | Root cause |\n    41→|---------|-------|---------|------------|\n    42→| A. Corrupted spillover — title absent | 5 | empty | `findBurstEnd` skips spillover marker but doesn't scan far enough for the title |\n    43→| B. Heavy digit corruption — title rejected | 2 | empty | `repairOcrText` can't fix `w1th`, `D1p` (not in food dictionary) → corrupted title fails embedding scoring |\n    44→| C. Partial corruption — wrong body line | 3 | wrong | Same as B — partially-repaired title scores lower than a body text line |\n    45→| D. Section header before title | 3 | wrong/empty | First-after-preamble bonus isn't firing for all cases; pipe-delimited metadata followed by title not handled |\n    46→| E. Multi-line title truncated | 1 | partial | `VEGETABLES` is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so caps-coalescing refuses to merge it with preceding `LEMON HERB ROASTED` |\n    47→| F. Mid-recipe page start | 2 | wrong | `isTitleAbsentPage` checks first 3 lines for ingredients/instructions, but body text (prose) isn't detected |\n    48→\n    49→### What works well (do not change)\n    50→\n    51→- Pipeline architecture: candidate generation → hard filters → embedding scoring → multi-title assembly\n    52→- Dictionary-guided OCR repair mechanism (just needs a wider dictionary)\n    53→- Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title assembly (iteration 25 fix)\n    54→- Compound title dedup protection\n    55→- Bilingual detection (both ALL_CAPS and mixed-case variants)\n    56→- Real file accuracy: 100%\n    57→- Shorter-wins dedup rule (DO NOT CHANGE — see architecture.md warning)\n    58→\n    59→## Goals\n    60→\n    61→- Fix all 16 generated-file failures without regressing real files\n    62→- Keep changes minimal and localized within the existing pipeline stages\n    63→\n    64→## Non-Goals\n    65→\n    66→- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n    67→- Reworking the overall pipeline structure\n    68→- Adding new generated test files\n    69→- Changing the dedup logic\n    70→\n    71→---\n    72→\n    73→## Detailed Design\n    74→\n    75→### Fix 1: Expand OCR repair dictionary with common English words (Patterns B, C)\n    76→\n    77→**Root cause detail:** `repairOcrWord` only matches against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. Common\n    78→English words that appear in recipe titles — prepositions (`with`, `the`, `for`),\n    79→adjectives (`old`, `new`, `hot`), and short food terms (`dip`, `pie`, `jam`, `bun`) —\n    80→are missing. When these words contain OCR digits, repair fails and the candidate enters\n    81→embedding scoring with residual corruption.\n    82→\n    83→Tracing Pattern B failure `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n    84→- `Bra1sed` → `braised` ✓ (in dictionary)\n    85→- `Cod` → no digits, passes through ✓\n    86→- `w1th` → tries `with` (1→i) → NOT in dictionary → stays `w1th` ✗\n    87→- `Wh1te` → `white` ✓\n    88→- `W1ne` → `wine` ✓\n    89→\n    90→Result after repair: `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` — the residual `w1th` degrades\n    91→embedding quality enough to push the title below threshold.\n    92→\n    93→**Fix:** Add a `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` set to `food-dictionary.ts` containing ~50 words\n    94→that commonly appear in recipe titles but aren't food-specific:\n    95→\n    96→```typescript\n    97→// Common English words that appear in recipe titles (for OCR repair)\n    98→const COMMON_TITLE_WORDS: Set<string> = new Set([\n    99→  // Prepositions & conjunctions\n   100→  \"with\", \"from\", \"over\", \"under\",\n   101→  // Adjectives\n   102→  \"classic\", \"simple\", \"quick\", \"easy\", \"light\",\n   103→  \"thick\", \"thin\", \"crispy\", \"creamy\", \"spicy\",\n   104→  // Short food terms missing from main dictionary\n   105→  \"dip\", \"pie\", \"bun\", \"buns\", \"roll\", \"rolls\",\n   106→  \"jam\", \"jelly\", \"tart\", \"cake\", \"loaf\",\n   107→  \"soup\", \"stew\", \"hash\", \"bowl\", \"wrap\",\n   108→  // Polish common title words\n   109→  \"pieczony\", \"pieczone\", \"smażony\", \"smażone\",\n   110→  \"gotowany\", \"gotowane\", \"duszone\", \"duszony\",\n   111→  \"domowy\", \"domowe\", \"tradycyjny\", \"tradycyjne\",\n   112→]);\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→Merge this into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (or check both sets in `repairOcrWord`). The\n   116→simpler approach is to add these words directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`.\n   117→\n   118→**Expected impact:** Fixes B (2) and C (3) = 5 failures. After full repair,\n   119→`Braised Cod with White Wine` scores correctly on embeddings and wins over body text.\n   120→\n   121→### Fix 2: Allow section-label words in multi-line title merges (Pattern E)\n   122→\n   123→**Root cause detail:** In the caps-coalescing loop (line ~510-548), the condition\n   124→`!isSectionLabel(next.text)` prevents `VEGETABLES` from merging with the preceding\n   125→`LEMON HERB ROASTED`. But `LEMON HERB ROASTED` is clearly an incomplete title\n   126→fragment (3 words, ends mid-phrase). The section-label check is correct in general\n   127→(prevent merging `SKŁADNIKI` into a title), but too aggressive for single words\n   128→that complete an obviously truncated preceding line.\n   129→\n   130→**Cross-iteration tension:** Iterations 18 and 22 deliberately added `\"vegetables\"`\n   131→(and other food-category words) to `SECTION_LABELS` to prevent standalone `VEGETABLES`\n   132→from being selected as a title. This fix relaxes that protection for merges while\n   133→preserving it for standalone candidates. The `\"placki\"` precedent from iteration 22\n   134→(removed from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely because it starts recipe titles) shows the\n   135→project already acknowledges that category words can legitimately appear in titles.\n   136→\n   137→**Fix:** Relax the section-label merge block when the **preceding merged text** is\n   138→short (≤ 4 words) and the next line is a single word. The heuristic: a short ALL_CAPS\n   139→fragment followed by a single ALL_CAPS word that happens to be a section label is more\n   140→likely a fragmented title than a title followed by a section header.\n   141→\n   142→```typescript\n   143→// In caps-coalescing loop, replace:\n   144→//   !isSectionLabel(next.text)\n   145→// with:\n   146→//   !isSectionLabel(next.text) ||\n   147→//   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4)\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→Additionally, check that the repaired form of the section label doesn't match either.\n   151→The existing code already checks `!isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))` — extend\n   152→the relaxation to also apply when this check would have blocked the merge.\n   153→\n   154→**Safety:** Only fires for single-word section labels following short ALL_CAPS\n   155→fragments. Multi-word section labels (`SPOSOB WYKONANIA`) are unaffected. And\n   156→`SKŁADNIKI` following a complete 5+ word title would NOT merge (the word count\n   157→guard prevents it). Standalone `VEGETABLES` as a candidate (without a preceding\n   158→short fragment) is still blocked by SECTION_LABELS — this relaxation only applies\n   159→to the merge path, not the standalone candidate filter.\n   160→\n   161→**Expected impact:** Fixes E (1) = 1 failure. `LEMON HERB ROASTED` + `VEGETABLES`\n   162→→ `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n   163→\n   164→### Fix 3: Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd` (Pattern A)\n   165→\n   166→**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\n   167→hard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\n   168→The `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex already includes `SPILLOVER` as a match, so\n   169→`findBurstEnd` detects the marker. However, after detecting the marker, `findBurstEnd`\n   170→looks for a separator (blank line or `====`) to determine where the preamble ends.\n   171→If the spillover content continues as body text without a clear separator,\n   172→`findBurstEnd` doesn't advance far enough. The title may be buried at line 10+ or\n   173→absent entirely, and the extractor gives up because no candidate emerges near the\n   174→(insufficiently advanced) burst end.\n   175→\n   176→**Note (iteration 25 context):** Iteration 25 analyzed this same pattern and noted\n   177→that `findBurstEnd` \"doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not\n   178→short), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" The core issue is\n   179→skip-distance, not marker detection.\n   180→\n   181→**Fix:** Two changes:\n   182→\n   183→1. Improve `findBurstEnd`'s post-marker skip logic. After detecting an overflow\n   184→   marker (including `SPILLOVER`), skip ALL subsequent lines until either:\n   185→   (a) a gap of ≥2 consecutive blank lines,\n   186→   (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   187→   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words (structural signal for a new recipe heading).\n   188→\n   189→   This replaces the current \"look for next blank line\" logic which fails when\n   190→   spillover body text continues without separators.\n   191→\n   192→2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   193→   preamble, relax the position preference — don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   194→   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   195→   anywhere in the document.\n   196→\n   197→   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   198→   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   199→   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   200→   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work.\n   201→\n   202→**Expected impact:** Fixes A (5) = 5 failures for cases where the title exists later\n   203→in the document. For cases where the title is truly absent (was on the previous page),\n   204→the extractor should return empty — which it already does when no candidates survive.\n   205→\n   206→### Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for Pattern D cases\n   207→\n   208→**Root cause detail:** The first-after-preamble bonus (line ~964-977) checks whether\n   209→ALL preceding lines were filtered or empty. For the Halibut case, `FISH & SEAFOOD`\n   210→is filtered as a section label, so the check should pass. But the bonus is only +0.08.\n   211→If the actual title (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`) has a weak rawScore against\n   212→the title reference embedding (it's a mixed-case description-like string), +0.08 may\n   213→not be enough to clear the threshold.\n   214→\n   215→For Ogórkowa Zupa, the pipe-delimited metadata line is correctly filtered, and\n   216→`OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` at position 2 should be an ALL_CAPS structural heading candidate.\n   217→The issue may be that `OGÓRKOWA` contains the OCR-challenging `Ó` which could affect\n   218→embedding quality, or that the first-after-preamble check doesn't fire because there's\n   219→a non-filtered blank line at position 1.\n   220→\n   221→**Fix:** Two adjustments:\n   222→\n   223→1. Make the first-after-preamble check more robust by also treating blank lines as\n   224→   \"filtered\" (they already are treated as empty, but ensure the check includes them):\n   225→\n   226→   ```typescript\n   227→   const allPrecedingFiltered = lines\n   228→     .slice(0, firstCandidate.position)\n   229→     .every((line) => {\n   230→       const trimmed = line.trim();\n   231→       return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);\n   232→     });\n   233→   ```\n   234→\n   235→   The addition of `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` catches cases where a section label\n   236→   passes hard filters at an earlier iteration's filter set but was added to\n   237→   `SECTION_LABELS` later without being added to `passesHardFilters`. (Currently\n   238→   `passesHardFilters` does check `isSectionLabel`, so this is a safety net.)\n   239→\n   240→2. Increase the first-after-preamble bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the filtered\n   241→   preamble contained a section label or metadata line (not just empty lines). This\n   242→   gives stronger positional evidence that the first surviving candidate IS the title.\n   243→\n   244→   **Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced the candidate-relative position\n   245→   bonus (~+0.08-0.12 for position 0 among surviving candidates). When both bonuses\n   246→   fire for the same candidate, the combined positional boost could reach ~+0.24.\n   247→   To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus\n   248→   and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive — if both apply, cap\n   249→   their combined contribution at +0.15.\n   250→\n   251→**Expected impact:** Fixes D (3) = 3 failures. The stronger bonus pushes\n   252→`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` and `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` above threshold.\n   253→\n   254→### Fix 5: Improve mid-recipe page detection (Pattern F)\n   255→\n   256→**Root cause detail:** `isTitleAbsentPage` checks if the first 3 non-empty lines are\n   257→all ingredients or cooking instructions. But:\n   258→\n   259→- Sweet Potato Salad: starts with ingredient lines → `isTitleAbsentPage` should detect\n   260→  this. Yet the extractor returns `½ red onion, thinly sliced`. This means either\n   261→  `isTitleAbsentPage` returned false (not all 3 lines matched), or the title-absent\n   262→  guard (line ~1171) didn't fully filter the result.\n   263→\n   264→  Looking at the guard: it requires `rawScore >= 0.10` AND `position <= 2`. An\n   265→  ingredient line at position 0-2 could survive if it has rawScore ≥ 0.10 — which\n   266→  shouldn't happen for ingredients, but `½ red onion, thinly sliced` might be short\n   267→  enough to have a mediocre (not terrible) embedding score.\n   268→\n   269→  **Hmm** — but `½ red onion, thinly sliced` should be caught by `looksLikeIngredient`\n   270→  (has `½` = starts with number? No — `½` is not matched by `/^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?\\d/`\n   271→  because `½` is not `\\d`). This is a bug in `startsWithNumber` — Unicode fractions\n   272→  aren't matched.\n   273→\n   274→- Mushroom Risotto: starts with `Reduce heat and stir...` — prose body text, not\n   275→  ingredients. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should catch this (starts with `Reduce`),\n   276→  but `Reduce` is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`. Another missing verb.\n   277→\n   278→**Fix:**\n   279→\n   280→1. Add Unicode fraction characters to `startsWithNumber`:\n   281→   ```typescript\n   282→   function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n   283→     return /^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?[\\d½⅓⅔¼¾⅕⅖⅗⅘⅙⅚⅛⅜⅝⅞]/.test(line);\n   284→   }\n   285→   ```\n   286→\n   287→2. Add missing cooking verbs to `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: `reduce`, `bring`,\n   288→   `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`. Wait — checking line 317... `reduce`,\n   289→   `bring`, `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`, `scatter`, `score`, `pat`, `rub`,\n   290→   `skim`, `strain`, `heat`, `discard`, `rest`, `marinate`, `wrap` — these are\n   291→   ALREADY in the regex (added in iteration 24). Let me re-read...\n   292→\n   293→   Yes, line 317 includes `reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form|scatter|score|pat|rub|skim|strain|heat|discard|rest|marinate|wrap`. So `reduce` IS covered.\n   294→\n   295→   The issue with Mushroom Risotto might be different. `Reduce heat and stir...` — the\n   296→   verb is `Reduce` which IS in the pattern. So `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should\n   297→   return true for this line. And `isTitleAbsentPage` checks `looksLikeCookingInstruction`.\n   298→\n   299→   Let me re-examine: the requirement is that ALL of the first 3 non-empty lines match.\n   300→   If one of the 3 lines is neither ingredient nor instruction (e.g., a descriptive\n   301→   sentence), the check fails. That's probably what's happening.\n   302→\n   303→   **Alternative approach for Mushroom Risotto:** The real fix is that when the page\n   304→   contains no title in the early lines AND a clear recipe title appears deep in the\n   305→   document (position 20+), the title likely belongs to a different recipe. The\n   306→   title-absent guard already filters `position <= 2`, which should prevent picking\n   307→   up `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` from position 20+. But the feedback says it IS\n   308→   being extracted — so maybe the `titleAbsent` flag isn't being set.\n   309→\n   310→   **Fix for `isTitleAbsentPage`:** Add body-prose detection alongside ingredient\n   311→   and cooking-instruction checks. A line starting with a lowercase letter and having\n   312→   4+ words is prose continuation, not a title:\n   313→\n   314→   ```typescript\n   315→   function isBodyProse(line: string): boolean {\n   316→     return /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(line) && wordCount(line) >= 4;\n   317→   }\n   318→\n   319→   function isTitleAbsentPage(lines: Array<string>): boolean {\n   320→     const nonEmptyLines = lines.map(l => l.trim()).filter(l => l.length > 0);\n   321→     if (nonEmptyLines.length < 3) return false;\n   322→     const first3 = nonEmptyLines.slice(0, 3);\n   323→     return first3.every(line =>\n   324→       looksLikeIngredient(line) ||\n   325→       looksLikeCookingInstruction(line) ||\n   326→       isBodyProse(line)\n   327→     );\n   328→   }\n   329→   ```\n   330→\n   331→   Keep the strict \"all 3\" threshold (not \"2 of 3\") to minimize false positives.\n   332→   Recipe titles are capitalized, so lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator.\n   333→\n   334→   **Cross-iteration tension with iteration 23:** Iteration 23 added a last-resort\n   335→   fallback that returns the first hard-filter-passing candidate when embedding-based\n   336→   logic produces nothing. This pulls in the opposite direction — iteration 23 made\n   337→   the system more aggressive about returning *something*, while this fix makes it\n   338→   more aggressive about returning *nothing* for mid-recipe pages.\n   339→\n   340→   **Resolution:** `isTitleAbsentPage` should raise the extraction threshold (require\n   341→   higher rawScore + early position), NOT act as a hard gate that prevents all\n   342→   extraction. If `isTitleAbsentPage` is true but a position-0 candidate passes hard\n   343→   filters with rawScore ≥ 0.10, the last-resort fallback from iteration 23 should\n   344→   still be allowed to fire. This ensures that pages which genuinely start with a\n   345→   title (but happen to have body-prose-like lines nearby) aren't suppressed.\n   346→\n   347→**Expected impact:** Fixes F (2) = 2 failures.\n   348→\n   349→---\n   350→\n   351→## Summary of Changes\n   352→\n   353→### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   354→\n   355→| Change | Description |\n   356→|--------|-------------|\n   357→| Add common title words | ~50 words: prepositions, adjectives, short food terms |\n   358→\n   359→### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   360→\n   361→| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n   362→|--------|----------|----------------|\n   363→| Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | `buildCandidates`, caps-coalescing loop (~line 525) | E |\n   364→| Improve post-marker skip distance (marker already detected; fix skip logic) | `findBurstEnd` (~line 400) | A |\n   365→| Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for section-label preambles | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` (~line 964) | D |\n   366→| Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber` | `startsWithNumber` (~line 101) | F |\n   367→| Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage` | `isTitleAbsentPage` (~line 338) | F |\n   368→\n   369→### No changes to\n   370→\n   371→- Embedding model, reference strings, or scoring formula\n   372→- Dedup logic (shorter-wins rule)\n   373→- Multi-title assembly logic\n   374→- Bilingual detection\n   375→- Threshold computation\n   376→\n   377→---\n   378→\n   379→## Testing Strategy\n   380→\n   381→### Primary validation\n   382→\n   383→Run `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` and confirm:\n   384→- All 16 generated-file failures are fixed\n   385→- All 11 real files continue to pass (no regressions)\n   386→\n   387→### Unit test cases to add\n   388→\n   389→1. **OCR repair with common words:** Input `\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"` →\n   390→   repaired to `\"Braised Cod with White Wine\"`. Validates dictionary expansion.\n   391→\n   392→2. **Section-label merge in title:** Input with `LEMON HERB ROASTED` on line 1 and\n   393→   `VEGETABLES` on line 2 → merged as `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n   394→\n   395→3. **Unicode fraction ingredient detection:** `\"½ red onion, thinly sliced\"` →\n   396→   `startsWithNumber` returns true.\n   397→\n   398→4. **Body-prose title-absent detection:** Input starting with `\"Reduce heat and stir...\"`\n   399→   followed by more body text → `isTitleAbsentPage` returns true.\n   400→\n   401→5. **Spillover skip:** Input with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` followed by body text\n   402→   then a title at line 10 → title correctly extracted.\n   403→\n   404→### Edge cases to verify\n   405→\n   406→- A recipe titled exactly `\"Vegetable Soup\"` where `\"VEGETABLES\"` appears on its own\n   407→  line → should NOT be merged if preceded by 5+ word title (word count guard)\n   408→- A recipe starting with `\"½ cup\"` as the first ingredient but with a title on line 0\n   409→  → `isTitleAbsentPage` should NOT fire because line 0 has the title\n   410→- Single-word section label `\"SKŁADNIKI\"` at line 2 following a complete title at\n   411→  line 0 → should NOT merge (preceding merged text would be ≥5 words)\n   412→- Page with body prose on lines 0-2 but a valid title at position 0 that passes hard\n   413→  filters → `isTitleAbsentPage` must NOT suppress extraction (iteration 23 last-resort\n   414→  fallback must still fire)\n   415→\n   416→---\n   417→\n   418→## Performance Considerations\n   419→\n   420→All changes are to string matching and heuristic checks. No additional embedding calls.\n   421→The dictionary expansion adds ~50 words to a Set lookup (O(1)). No performance impact.\n   422→\n   423→---\n   424→\n   425→## Security Considerations\n   426→\n   427→None. All changes are local text processing.\n   428→\n   429→---\n   430→\n   431→## Implementation Phases\n   432→\n   433→### Phase 1: Core fixes (single change set)\n   434→\n   435→1. Add common title words to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   436→2. Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations\n   437→3. Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber`\n   438→4. Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage`\n   439→5. Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd`\n   440→6. Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus\n   441→\n   442→All changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. Run the evaluation\n   443→harness once after all changes to verify.\n   444→\n   445→---\n   446→\n   447→## Risk Assessment\n   448→\n   449→| Change | Risk | Mitigation |\n   450→|--------|------|------------|\n   451→| Dictionary expansion | Over-correction: common words might cause false repairs in non-title contexts | Only triggers when word contains OCR-artifact chars; dictionary match is positive signal |\n   452→| Section-label merge relaxation | Could merge section labels into titles; partially reverses iteration 18/22 protections | Guarded by word count (preceding ≤4 words, next = single word); multi-word labels unaffected; standalone candidates still blocked |\n   453→| Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | False positives: pages with lowercase titles | Recipe titles are capitalized; lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator |\n   454→| First-after-preamble bonus increase | Could over-boost when combined with iter-24 candidate-relative position bonus | Cap combined positional boost at +0.15; only fires when all preceding lines were filtered |\n   455→\n   456→---\n   457→\n   458→## Open Questions\n   459→\n   460→1. **Should common title words go into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or a separate set?**\n   461→   Adding to `FOOD_DICTIONARY` is simpler (one lookup). A separate set keeps the\n   462→   dictionary semantically focused. **Recommendation:** Add directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   463→   — the dictionary's purpose is OCR repair, not food taxonomy.\n   464→\n   465→2. **Should the `isTitleAbsentPage` body-prose threshold be \"all 3\" or \"2 of 3\"?**\n   466→   \"All 3\" is safer (fewer false positives). \"2 of 3\" catches more mid-recipe pages.\n   467→   **Recommendation:** Keep \"all 3\" with the expanded detection (ingredients + instructions\n   468→   + body prose). If that doesn't catch all Pattern F cases, relax to \"2 of 3\".\n   469→\n   470→3. **Spillover handling: how far should `findBurstEnd` skip?** Currently it looks for\n   471→   the next blank line or separator after the marker. For spillover, the body text may\n   472→   continue for many lines without a clear separator. **Recommendation:** Skip until\n   473→   either (a) ≥2 consecutive blank lines, (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   474→   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words (likely the next recipe title).\n   475→\n   476→---\n   477→\n   478→## References\n   479→\n   480→- Iteration 26 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/feedback.md`\n   481→- Iteration 25 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md`\n   482→- Pipeline architecture: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n   483→- Accuracy history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n   484→- Food dictionary: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   485→- Title extractor: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   486→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe3f33e3-f5c0-4e4f-b865-ef8c5a90ce70","uuid":"709d3e2f-baa8-4dcf-b6d0-428a517df46c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 26 → 27 Improvement Plan\n\n## Title\n\nFix generated-file title extraction: OCR repair gaps, section-label merge blocking, and spillover handling\n\n## Status\n\nDraft\n\n## Authors\n\nClaude — 2026-03-17\n\n## Overview\n\nIteration 26 has 0 real-file failures and 16 generated-file failures across 6 patterns.\nReal accuracy is 100% (11/11). Combined accuracy is 85.6%.\n\nThe failures share two root causes:\n\n1. **OCR repair has blind spots** — the food dictionary lacks common English words\n   (`with`, `the`, `and`, `dip`, `pie`), so `repairOcrWord` can't fix them. Partially-\n   repaired titles like `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` score poorly on embeddings and\n   get skipped.\n\n2. **Structural heuristics are too rigid** — section labels block multi-line title\n   merges even when the label is clearly a title continuation; spillover markers don't\n   trigger a wider scan; and mid-recipe pages aren't reliably detected when body text\n   precedes ingredients.\n\nThe fix addresses both causes with targeted changes: expand the OCR repair dictionary,\nrelax section-label merge blocking for title continuations, and improve spillover/\nmid-recipe detection. The pipeline architecture is unchanged.\n\n## Background / Problem Statement\n\n### Failure breakdown\n\n| Pattern | Count | Returns | Root cause |\n|---------|-------|---------|------------|\n| A. Corrupted spillover — title absent | 5 | empty | `findBurstEnd` skips spillover marker but doesn't scan far enough for the title |\n| B. Heavy digit corruption — title rejected | 2 | empty | `repairOcrText` can't fix `w1th`, `D1p` (not in food dictionary) → corrupted title fails embedding scoring |\n| C. Partial corruption — wrong body line | 3 | wrong | Same as B — partially-repaired title scores lower than a body text line |\n| D. Section header before title | 3 | wrong/empty | First-after-preamble bonus isn't firing for all cases; pipe-delimited metadata followed by title not handled |\n| E. Multi-line title truncated | 1 | partial | `VEGETABLES` is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so caps-coalescing refuses to merge it with preceding `LEMON HERB ROASTED` |\n| F. Mid-recipe page start | 2 | wrong | `isTitleAbsentPage` checks first 3 lines for ingredients/instructions, but body text (prose) isn't detected |\n\n### What works well (do not change)\n\n- Pipeline architecture: candidate generation → hard filters → embedding scoring → multi-title assembly\n- Dictionary-guided OCR repair mechanism (just needs a wider dictionary)\n- Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title assembly (iteration 25 fix)\n- Compound title dedup protection\n- Bilingual detection (both ALL_CAPS and mixed-case variants)\n- Real file accuracy: 100%\n- Shorter-wins dedup rule (DO NOT CHANGE — see architecture.md warning)\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix all 16 generated-file failures without regressing real files\n- Keep changes minimal and localized within the existing pipeline stages\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n- Reworking the overall pipeline structure\n- Adding new generated test files\n- Changing the dedup logic\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Design\n\n### Fix 1: Expand OCR repair dictionary with common English words (Patterns B, C)\n\n**Root cause detail:** `repairOcrWord` only matches against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. Common\nEnglish words that appear in recipe titles — prepositions (`with`, `the`, `for`),\nadjectives (`old`, `new`, `hot`), and short food terms (`dip`, `pie`, `jam`, `bun`) —\nare missing. When these words contain OCR digits, repair fails and the candidate enters\nembedding scoring with residual corruption.\n\nTracing Pattern B failure `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n- `Bra1sed` → `braised` ✓ (in dictionary)\n- `Cod` → no digits, passes through ✓\n- `w1th` → tries `with` (1→i) → NOT in dictionary → stays `w1th` ✗\n- `Wh1te` → `white` ✓\n- `W1ne` → `wine` ✓\n\nResult after repair: `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` — the residual `w1th` degrades\nembedding quality enough to push the title below threshold.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` set to `food-dictionary.ts` containing ~50 words\nthat commonly appear in recipe titles but aren't food-specific:\n\n```typescript\n// Common English words that appear in recipe titles (for OCR repair)\nconst COMMON_TITLE_WORDS: Set<string> = new Set([\n  // Prepositions & conjunctions\n  \"with\", \"from\", \"over\", \"under\",\n  // Adjectives\n  \"classic\", \"simple\", \"quick\", \"easy\", \"light\",\n  \"thick\", \"thin\", \"crispy\", \"creamy\", \"spicy\",\n  // Short food terms missing from main dictionary\n  \"dip\", \"pie\", \"bun\", \"buns\", \"roll\", \"rolls\",\n  \"jam\", \"jelly\", \"tart\", \"cake\", \"loaf\",\n  \"soup\", \"stew\", \"hash\", \"bowl\", \"wrap\",\n  // Polish common title words\n  \"pieczony\", \"pieczone\", \"smażony\", \"smażone\",\n  \"gotowany\", \"gotowane\", \"duszone\", \"duszony\",\n  \"domowy\", \"domowe\", \"tradycyjny\", \"tradycyjne\",\n]);\n```\n\nMerge this into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (or check both sets in `repairOcrWord`). The\nsimpler approach is to add these words directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes B (2) and C (3) = 5 failures. After full repair,\n`Braised Cod with White Wine` scores correctly on embeddings and wins over body text.\n\n### Fix 2: Allow section-label words in multi-line title merges (Pattern E)\n\n**Root cause detail:** In the caps-coalescing loop (line ~510-548), the condition\n`!isSectionLabel(next.text)` prevents `VEGETABLES` from merging with the preceding\n`LEMON HERB ROASTED`. But `LEMON HERB ROASTED` is clearly an incomplete title\nfragment (3 words, ends mid-phrase). The section-label check is correct in general\n(prevent merging `SKŁADNIKI` into a title), but too aggressive for single words\nthat complete an obviously truncated preceding line.\n\n**Cross-iteration tension:** Iterations 18 and 22 deliberately added `\"vegetables\"`\n(and other food-category words) to `SECTION_LABELS` to prevent standalone `VEGETABLES`\nfrom being selected as a title. This fix relaxes that protection for merges while\npreserving it for standalone candidates. The `\"placki\"` precedent from iteration 22\n(removed from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely because it starts recipe titles) shows the\nproject already acknowledges that category words can legitimately appear in titles.\n\n**Fix:** Relax the section-label merge block when the **preceding merged text** is\nshort (≤ 4 words) and the next line is a single word. The heuristic: a short ALL_CAPS\nfragment followed by a single ALL_CAPS word that happens to be a section label is more\nlikely a fragmented title than a title followed by a section header.\n\n```typescript\n// In caps-coalescing loop, replace:\n//   !isSectionLabel(next.text)\n// with:\n//   !isSectionLabel(next.text) ||\n//   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4)\n```\n\nAdditionally, check that the repaired form of the section label doesn't match either.\nThe existing code already checks `!isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))` — extend\nthe relaxation to also apply when this check would have blocked the merge.\n\n**Safety:** Only fires for single-word section labels following short ALL_CAPS\nfragments. Multi-word section labels (`SPOSOB WYKONANIA`) are unaffected. And\n`SKŁADNIKI` following a complete 5+ word title would NOT merge (the word count\nguard prevents it). Standalone `VEGETABLES` as a candidate (without a preceding\nshort fragment) is still blocked by SECTION_LABELS — this relaxation only applies\nto the merge path, not the standalone candidate filter.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes E (1) = 1 failure. `LEMON HERB ROASTED` + `VEGETABLES`\n→ `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n\n### Fix 3: Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd` (Pattern A)\n\n**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\nhard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\nThe `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex already includes `SPILLOVER` as a match, so\n`findBurstEnd` detects the marker. However, after detecting the marker, `findBurstEnd`\nlooks for a separator (blank line or `====`) to determine where the preamble ends.\nIf the spillover content continues as body text without a clear separator,\n`findBurstEnd` doesn't advance far enough. The title may be buried at line 10+ or\nabsent entirely, and the extractor gives up because no candidate emerges near the\n(insufficiently advanced) burst end.\n\n**Note (iteration 25 context):** Iteration 25 analyzed this same pattern and noted\nthat `findBurstEnd` \"doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not\nshort), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" The core issue is\nskip-distance, not marker detection.\n\n**Fix:** Two changes:\n\n1. Improve `findBurstEnd`'s post-marker skip logic. After detecting an overflow\n   marker (including `SPILLOVER`), skip ALL subsequent lines until either:\n   (a) a gap of ≥2 consecutive blank lines,\n   (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words (structural signal for a new recipe heading).\n\n   This replaces the current \"look for next blank line\" logic which fails when\n   spillover body text continues without separators.\n\n2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   preamble, relax the position preference — don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   anywhere in the document.\n\n   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes A (5) = 5 failures for cases where the title exists later\nin the document. For cases where the title is truly absent (was on the previous page),\nthe extractor should return empty — which it already does when no candidates survive.\n\n### Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for Pattern D cases\n\n**Root cause detail:** The first-after-preamble bonus (line ~964-977) checks whether\nALL preceding lines were filtered or empty. For the Halibut case, `FISH & SEAFOOD`\nis filtered as a section label, so the check should pass. But the bonus is only +0.08.\nIf the actual title (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`) has a weak rawScore against\nthe title reference embedding (it's a mixed-case description-like string), +0.08 may\nnot be enough to clear the threshold.\n\nFor Ogórkowa Zupa, the pipe-delimited metadata line is correctly filtered, and\n`OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` at position 2 should be an ALL_CAPS structural heading candidate.\nThe issue may be that `OGÓRKOWA` contains the OCR-challenging `Ó` which could affect\nembedding quality, or that the first-after-preamble check doesn't fire because there's\na non-filtered blank line at position 1.\n\n**Fix:** Two adjustments:\n\n1. Make the first-after-preamble check more robust by also treating blank lines as\n   \"filtered\" (they already are treated as empty, but ensure the check includes them):\n\n   ```typescript\n   const allPrecedingFiltered = lines\n     .slice(0, firstCandidate.position)\n     .every((line) => {\n       const trimmed = line.trim();\n       return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);\n     });\n   ```\n\n   The addition of `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` catches cases where a section label\n   passes hard filters at an earlier iteration's filter set but was added to\n   `SECTION_LABELS` later without being added to `passesHardFilters`. (Currently\n   `passesHardFilters` does check `isSectionLabel`, so this is a safety net.)\n\n2. Increase the first-after-preamble bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the filtered\n   preamble contained a section label or metadata line (not just empty lines). This\n   gives stronger positional evidence that the first surviving candidate IS the title.\n\n   **Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced the candidate-relative position\n   bonus (~+0.08-0.12 for position 0 among surviving candidates). When both bonuses\n   fire for the same candidate, the combined positional boost could reach ~+0.24.\n   To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus\n   and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive — if both apply, cap\n   their combined contribution at +0.15.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes D (3) = 3 failures. The stronger bonus pushes\n`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` and `OGÓRKOWA ZUPA` above threshold.\n\n### Fix 5: Improve mid-recipe page detection (Pattern F)\n\n**Root cause detail:** `isTitleAbsentPage` checks if the first 3 non-empty lines are\nall ingredients or cooking instructions. But:\n\n- Sweet Potato Salad: starts with ingredient lines → `isTitleAbsentPage` should detect\n  this. Yet the extractor returns `½ red onion, thinly sliced`. This means either\n  `isTitleAbsentPage` returned false (not all 3 lines matched), or the title-absent\n  guard (line ~1171) didn't fully filter the result.\n\n  Looking at the guard: it requires `rawScore >= 0.10` AND `position <= 2`. An\n  ingredient line at position 0-2 could survive if it has rawScore ≥ 0.10 — which\n  shouldn't happen for ingredients, but `½ red onion, thinly sliced` might be short\n  enough to have a mediocre (not terrible) embedding score.\n\n  **Hmm** — but `½ red onion, thinly sliced` should be caught by `looksLikeIngredient`\n  (has `½` = starts with number? No — `½` is not matched by `/^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?\\d/`\n  because `½` is not `\\d`). This is a bug in `startsWithNumber` — Unicode fractions\n  aren't matched.\n\n- Mushroom Risotto: starts with `Reduce heat and stir...` — prose body text, not\n  ingredients. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should catch this (starts with `Reduce`),\n  but `Reduce` is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`. Another missing verb.\n\n**Fix:**\n\n1. Add Unicode fraction characters to `startsWithNumber`:\n   ```typescript\n   function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n     return /^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?[\\d½⅓⅔¼¾⅕⅖⅗⅘⅙⅚⅛⅜⅝⅞]/.test(line);\n   }\n   ```\n\n2. Add missing cooking verbs to `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: `reduce`, `bring`,\n   `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`. Wait — checking line 317... `reduce`,\n   `bring`, `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`, `scatter`, `score`, `pat`, `rub`,\n   `skim`, `strain`, `heat`, `discard`, `rest`, `marinate`, `wrap` — these are\n   ALREADY in the regex (added in iteration 24). Let me re-read...\n\n   Yes, line 317 includes `reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form|scatter|score|pat|rub|skim|strain|heat|discard|rest|marinate|wrap`. So `reduce` IS covered.\n\n   The issue with Mushroom Risotto might be different. `Reduce heat and stir...` — the\n   verb is `Reduce` which IS in the pattern. So `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should\n   return true for this line. And `isTitleAbsentPage` checks `looksLikeCookingInstruction`.\n\n   Let me re-examine: the requirement is that ALL of the first 3 non-empty lines match.\n   If one of the 3 lines is neither ingredient nor instruction (e.g., a descriptive\n   sentence), the check fails. That's probably what's happening.\n\n   **Alternative approach for Mushroom Risotto:** The real fix is that when the page\n   contains no title in the early lines AND a clear recipe title appears deep in the\n   document (position 20+), the title likely belongs to a different recipe. The\n   title-absent guard already filters `position <= 2`, which should prevent picking\n   up `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` from position 20+. But the feedback says it IS\n   being extracted — so maybe the `titleAbsent` flag isn't being set.\n\n   **Fix for `isTitleAbsentPage`:** Add body-prose detection alongside ingredient\n   and cooking-instruction checks. A line starting with a lowercase letter and having\n   4+ words is prose continuation, not a title:\n\n   ```typescript\n   function isBodyProse(line: string): boolean {\n     return /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(line) && wordCount(line) >= 4;\n   }\n\n   function isTitleAbsentPage(lines: Array<string>): boolean {\n     const nonEmptyLines = lines.map(l => l.trim()).filter(l => l.length > 0);\n     if (nonEmptyLines.length < 3) return false;\n     const first3 = nonEmptyLines.slice(0, 3);\n     return first3.every(line =>\n       looksLikeIngredient(line) ||\n       looksLikeCookingInstruction(line) ||\n       isBodyProse(line)\n     );\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Keep the strict \"all 3\" threshold (not \"2 of 3\") to minimize false positives.\n   Recipe titles are capitalized, so lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator.\n\n   **Cross-iteration tension with iteration 23:** Iteration 23 added a last-resort\n   fallback that returns the first hard-filter-passing candidate when embedding-based\n   logic produces nothing. This pulls in the opposite direction — iteration 23 made\n   the system more aggressive about returning *something*, while this fix makes it\n   more aggressive about returning *nothing* for mid-recipe pages.\n\n   **Resolution:** `isTitleAbsentPage` should raise the extraction threshold (require\n   higher rawScore + early position), NOT act as a hard gate that prevents all\n   extraction. If `isTitleAbsentPage` is true but a position-0 candidate passes hard\n   filters with rawScore ≥ 0.10, the last-resort fallback from iteration 23 should\n   still be allowed to fire. This ensures that pages which genuinely start with a\n   title (but happen to have body-prose-like lines nearby) aren't suppressed.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes F (2) = 2 failures.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Changes\n\n### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n\n| Change | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| Add common title words | ~50 words: prepositions, adjectives, short food terms |\n\n### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\n| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n|--------|----------|----------------|\n| Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | `buildCandidates`, caps-coalescing loop (~line 525) | E |\n| Improve post-marker skip distance (marker already detected; fix skip logic) | `findBurstEnd` (~line 400) | A |\n| Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for section-label preambles | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` (~line 964) | D |\n| Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber` | `startsWithNumber` (~line 101) | F |\n| Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage` | `isTitleAbsentPage` (~line 338) | F |\n\n### No changes to\n\n- Embedding model, reference strings, or scoring formula\n- Dedup logic (shorter-wins rule)\n- Multi-title assembly logic\n- Bilingual detection\n- Threshold computation\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Primary validation\n\nRun `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` and confirm:\n- All 16 generated-file failures are fixed\n- All 11 real files continue to pass (no regressions)\n\n### Unit test cases to add\n\n1. **OCR repair with common words:** Input `\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"` →\n   repaired to `\"Braised Cod with White Wine\"`. Validates dictionary expansion.\n\n2. **Section-label merge in title:** Input with `LEMON HERB ROASTED` on line 1 and\n   `VEGETABLES` on line 2 → merged as `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n\n3. **Unicode fraction ingredient detection:** `\"½ red onion, thinly sliced\"` →\n   `startsWithNumber` returns true.\n\n4. **Body-prose title-absent detection:** Input starting with `\"Reduce heat and stir...\"`\n   followed by more body text → `isTitleAbsentPage` returns true.\n\n5. **Spillover skip:** Input with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` followed by body text\n   then a title at line 10 → title correctly extracted.\n\n### Edge cases to verify\n\n- A recipe titled exactly `\"Vegetable Soup\"` where `\"VEGETABLES\"` appears on its own\n  line → should NOT be merged if preceded by 5+ word title (word count guard)\n- A recipe starting with `\"½ cup\"` as the first ingredient but with a title on line 0\n  → `isTitleAbsentPage` should NOT fire because line 0 has the title\n- Single-word section label `\"SKŁADNIKI\"` at line 2 following a complete title at\n  line 0 → should NOT merge (preceding merged text would be ≥5 words)\n- Page with body prose on lines 0-2 but a valid title at position 0 that passes hard\n  filters → `isTitleAbsentPage` must NOT suppress extraction (iteration 23 last-resort\n  fallback must still fire)\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nAll changes are to string matching and heuristic checks. No additional embedding calls.\nThe dictionary expansion adds ~50 words to a Set lookup (O(1)). No performance impact.\n\n---\n\n## Security Considerations\n\nNone. All changes are local text processing.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Core fixes (single change set)\n\n1. Add common title words to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n2. Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations\n3. Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber`\n4. Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage`\n5. Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd`\n6. Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus\n\nAll changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. Run the evaluation\nharness once after all changes to verify.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Assessment\n\n| Change | Risk | Mitigation |\n|--------|------|------------|\n| Dictionary expansion | Over-correction: common words might cause false repairs in non-title contexts | Only triggers when word contains OCR-artifact chars; dictionary match is positive signal |\n| Section-label merge relaxation | Could merge section labels into titles; partially reverses iteration 18/22 protections | Guarded by word count (preceding ≤4 words, next = single word); multi-word labels unaffected; standalone candidates still blocked |\n| Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | False positives: pages with lowercase titles | Recipe titles are capitalized; lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator |\n| First-after-preamble bonus increase | Could over-boost when combined with iter-24 candidate-relative position bonus | Cap combined positional boost at +0.15; only fires when all preceding lines were filtered |\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Should common title words go into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or a separate set?**\n   Adding to `FOOD_DICTIONARY` is simpler (one lookup). A separate set keeps the\n   dictionary semantically focused. **Recommendation:** Add directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   — the dictionary's purpose is OCR repair, not food taxonomy.\n\n2. **Should the `isTitleAbsentPage` body-prose threshold be \"all 3\" or \"2 of 3\"?**\n   \"All 3\" is safer (fewer false positives). \"2 of 3\" catches more mid-recipe pages.\n   **Recommendation:** Keep \"all 3\" with the expanded detection (ingredients + instructions\n   + body prose). If that doesn't catch all Pattern F cases, relax to \"2 of 3\".\n\n3. **Spillover handling: how far should `findBurstEnd` skip?** Currently it looks for\n   the next blank line or separator after the marker. For spillover, the body text may\n   continue for many lines without a clear separator. **Recommendation:** Skip until\n   either (a) ≥2 consecutive blank lines, (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with ≥2 words (likely the next recipe title).\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration 26 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/feedback.md`\n- Iteration 25 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md`\n- Pipeline architecture: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n- Accuracy history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n- Food dictionary: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n- Title extractor: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n","numLines":486,"startLine":1,"totalLines":486}}}
